{"term":"1957","caseName":"City of Chicago v. Atchison, Topeka & Santa Fe Railway Company","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1957/103","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument, Part 1: City of Chicago v. Atchison, Topeka & Santa Fe Railway Company - March 05, 1958 (103)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13433","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 103, City of Chicago, Petitioner versus the Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway Company.","start":0,"stop":31.326,"duration":31.33}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":31.326,"stop":36.57,"duration":5.24}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Grossman, you may proceed.","start":36.57,"stop":38.982,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"This case is here by writ of certiorari to the Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit.","start":38.982,"stop":47.361,"duration":8.38},{"text":"The suit was instituted in the United States District Court for a declaratory judgment and injunction by 21 frontline railroads operating to and from the City of Chicago in the interstate commerce and in the intrastate commerce.","start":47.361,"stop":68.925,"duration":21.56},{"text":"And the respondent, Railroad Transfer Service, Incorporated hereafter called “Transfer” for short, an uncertified motor carrier transferring passengers between terminal facilities of the various railroads of which there were I think eight in number in the City of Chicago.","start":68.925,"stop":108.016,"duration":39.09},{"text":"None of the railroads pass through the City of Chicago.","start":108.016,"stop":112.751,"duration":4.73},{"text":"There are eight terminals.","start":112.751,"stop":115.102,"duration":2.35},{"text":"Two of them on the west side of the Chicago River and six of them on the south and east side of the Chicago River, some distance south.","start":115.102,"stop":128.609,"duration":13.51},{"text":"The distance between the terminals vary from about a quarter of a mile to two miles distance.","start":128.609,"stop":143.171,"duration":14.56},{"text":"The case involved the construction or in the alternative as the pleading showed, the constitutionality of a city ordinance licensing the -- and regulating the use of the city streets by a motor vehicle for hire.","start":143.171,"stop":164.531,"duration":21.36},{"text":"The ordinance was known as Chapter 28 of the Municipal Court of Chicago which appears in the record at page -- beginning at page 171.","start":164.531,"stop":185.388,"duration":20.86},{"text":"Parmelee Transportation Company, another uncertified motor carrier intervened in the case.","start":185.388,"stop":199.095,"duration":13.71},{"text":"The Parmelee Company having -- have a contract of the railroads to operate at the -- the motor vehicles in the transfer of passengers in interstate commerce and intrastate commerce prior to the termination of that contract and the substitution of the Railroad Transfer Service.","start":199.095,"stop":231.596,"duration":32.5},{"text":"At that time until -- October 1, 1955, the terminal line had a contract arrangement with Parmelee as I said to furnish their service.","start":231.596,"stop":246.144,"duration":14.55},{"text":"But that operation was not limited to interstation service on through route railroad carriers.","start":246.144,"stop":254.476,"duration":8.33},{"text":"It also carried passengers for cash fares between terminal stations and from substations to hotels and other places within the central business district of the City of Chicago.","start":254.476,"stop":270.053,"duration":15.58},{"text":"Parmelee's operations were licensed as terminal vehicles under the city code relating to the public passenger vehicles, the licensing of public passenger vehicles.","start":270.053,"stop":286.951,"duration":16.9},{"text":"At that time, referring to the ordinance, a public passenger vehicle was defined by the code as a motor vehicle which is used for the transportation of passengers for hire accepting those devoted exclusively for funeral use or any operation of a Metropolitan Transit Authority or public utility under the laws of Illinois and the terminal vehicle was defined as a public passenger vehicle which is operated under contracts with the railroad and steamship companies exclusively for the transfer of passengers from terminal stations.","start":286.951,"stop":336.116,"duration":49.16},{"text":"Then Section 28-2 provided, it is unlawful for any person other than the Metropolitan Transit Authority or public utility to operate any vehicle or for any such person who is the owner of any vehicle to permit it to be operated on any public way for the transportation of passengers for hire from place to place within the corporate limits of the city except on a funeral trip unless it is licensed by the city as a public passenger vehicle.","start":336.116,"stop":375.7,"duration":39.58},{"text":"Those are the pertinent provisions of the ordinance which are involved in this case.","start":375.7,"stop":388.217,"duration":12.52},{"text":"Parmelee's operations as I said were licensed as terminal vehicles.","start":388.217,"stop":393.816,"duration":5.6},{"text":"Early in June 1955, the terminal lines notified Parmelee that their contractual arrangement would be terminated and other provision made for the transfer of passengers on through route tickets between terminal stations in Chicago.","start":393.816,"stop":415.006,"duration":21.19},{"text":"On July 26, 1955, the City Council passed an ordinance amending the city code by eliminating the requirement of a contractual arrangement with railroad companies to qualify terminal vehicles for license and limiting the number of such vehicles to those licensed unless after a public hearing is provided by the ordinance, public convenience and necessity require additional service of the character described.","start":415.006,"stop":454.412,"duration":39.41},{"text":"That provision in the ordinance was the -- in 2231-1 or 28 -- no, excuse me, it was 28-31.1, Chapter 28.","start":454.412,"stop":482.475,"duration":28.06},{"text":"It was amended at the same time that the definition of terminal vehicles was amended and also the section relating to the operation of terminal route vehicles which was limited to the central business district of the City of Chicago and it provided for a determination of public convenience and necessity prior to the issuance of any licenses for additional terminal vehicles.","start":482.475,"stop":516.576,"duration":34.1},{"text":"Now, Parmelee was then operating of course not in the transfer of passengers on through routes either in intrastate commerce or interstate commerce.","start":516.576,"stop":532.874,"duration":16.3},{"text":"It was operating after termination of its contract as a local public passenger vehicle.","start":532.874,"stop":543.381,"duration":10.51},{"text":"Still under license, transporting for a cash fare, passengers who happened to be at any railroad station to the hotels and to any destination which the passenger himself directed.","start":543.381,"stop":570.712,"duration":27.33},{"text":"The case was submitted in the District Court on the question of the construction of the contract both by the complaints and by the motion of the City of Chicago for summary judgment.","start":570.712,"stop":591.038,"duration":20.33},{"text":"The motion for summary judgment by the City of Chicago requested the Court to determine whether the Plaintiff by virtue of its contract with the plaintiff railroad company is operating its vehicles within the City of Chicago as exclusively as agent born in behalf of plaintiff railroads as public utilities under the law of Illinois, whether the plaintiff's operations are confined, the transportation of passengers on through route railroad and steamship transportation tickets between point out -- points outside of the corporate limits of the city in intrastate and interstate commerce.","start":591.038,"stop":648.176,"duration":57.14},{"text":"Now, the plaintiff in this case of course or the railroads and the Transfer Company, the Railroad Transfer Corporation under the new contract and whether said the plaintiff operates any vehicle on any public way for transportation of passenger for hire from place to place within the Court limits of the city as provided by Section 28-2 of the Municipal Court of Chicago, whether said plaintiff is operating terminal vehicles within the City of Chicago as defined in Section 28-1 of the Municipal Court of Chicago as amended in 1955, whether any of the said plaintiff's operations are in local transportation of passengers at rates of fares subject to Section 28-31.2 of the Municipal Court of Chicago.","start":648.176,"stop":710.257,"duration":62.08},{"text":"Now, I ought to make reference to 28-31.2 to indicate what kind of an operation it brought because under the powers of the City Council in the City of Chicago, the city has the right to determine the rates of fare of these passenger vehicles.","start":710.257,"stop":732.844,"duration":22.59},{"text":"And 28-31.2 provides that the rate of fare for local transportation of every passenger in terminal vehicles of the licensee shall be uniform regardless of the distance traveled provided that children under 12 years of age, when accompanied by an adult, shall be carried not more than half the fare.","start":732.844,"stop":756.545,"duration":23.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Grossman.","start":756.545,"stop":757.421,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":757.421,"stop":757.696,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Will it trouble you if I ask you, what it is that the lower court decided?","start":757.696,"stop":763.161,"duration":5.46}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"The lower -- the District Court --","start":763.161,"stop":764.169,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And that you want us to reverse?","start":764.169,"stop":766.353,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"-- yes, the District Court --","start":766.353,"stop":767.171,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That is my question.","start":767.171,"stop":767.859,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":767.859,"stop":768.633,"duration":0.77},{"text":"The District Court --","start":768.633,"stop":769.022,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- what is it that it decided that you think is wrong and what is it that you want us to decide?","start":769.022,"stop":773.686,"duration":4.66}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the Court of Appeals decided that the ordinance of 1955 was unconstitutional because Section 28-31.1 providing for the determination of public convenience and necessity was invalid as non-constitutional control by the city of interstate commerce.","start":773.686,"stop":814.859,"duration":41.17}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"With the consequence of transfer did not have to get a license with the government?","start":814.859,"stop":818.485,"duration":3.63}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"With the consequence of transfer would -- did not have to have a license.","start":818.485,"stop":821.981,"duration":3.5},{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":821.981,"stop":822.362,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That it applied for a license.","start":822.362,"stop":827.544,"duration":5.18}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"It had not applied for a license.","start":827.544,"stop":829.291,"duration":1.75},{"text":"And the point to that I make is that the Court of Appeals determined that 28-31.1, the public convenience and necessity provision gave Parmelee in effect a monopoly of the streets of the City of Chicago for the transfer of passengers between terminal stations.","start":829.291,"stop":855.411,"duration":26.12},{"text":"Whereas the point I make is that 28-31.1 was applicable to Parmelee because it was a local transportation facility after the enactment of the amendment, but 28-31.1 could not be applicable to the transport corporation because it was under the -- under its contract exclusively for the transfer of passengers between terminal stations in intrastate and interstate commerce.","start":855.411,"stop":899.29,"duration":43.88},{"text":"And so far as the intrastate commerce is concerned of course, there's no question about there ever having been required to have a license and even so far as the interstate commerce is concerned.","start":899.29,"stop":913.624,"duration":14.33},{"text":"They're -- they are subject to license.","start":913.624,"stop":917.07,"duration":3.45},{"text":"The power of the city to license that kind of an operation within the City of Chicago even though they are engaged in interstate commerce is there -- the question is did they exercise that power.","start":917.07,"stop":932.43,"duration":15.36},{"text":"Now, in the opinion of the Court of the Appeals, they -- the Court of Appeals decided what was the intent of the City Council in passing this ordinance of 1955 and permit me -- whether permit me to read and extract from the opinion which is in the appendix to my petition for certiorari.","start":932.43,"stop":967.341,"duration":34.91}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you contend Mr. Grossman the transfer of what make an application for license before they can raise your point?","start":967.341,"stop":973.112,"duration":5.77}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"I do.","start":973.112,"stop":975.182,"duration":2.07},{"text":"I -- I contend the transfer should make an application for a license and that the city authorities should pass upon the questions to whether they can be licensed or they cannot be licensed and if the decision were against the transfer company.","start":975.182,"stop":999.516,"duration":24.33},{"text":"The transfer company should then commence a suit in the state courts to have the state courts determine the meaning or the construction of the ordinance.","start":999.516,"stop":1014.351,"duration":14.84}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Has the -- have the state courts ever construe this ordinance?","start":1014.351,"stop":1018.491,"duration":4.14}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":1018.491,"stop":1020.605,"duration":2.11},{"text":"This ordinance has not been construed by the -- by the state court.","start":1020.605,"stop":1026.332,"duration":5.73},{"text":"This particular ordinance, I'm talking about the 1955 ordinance had not been construed.","start":1026.332,"stop":1030.335,"duration":4}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"One is -- one is in dispute here.","start":1030.335,"stop":1033.377,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the basic ordinance has been construed by the Supreme Court, yes.","start":1033.377,"stop":1038.556,"duration":5.18},{"text":"The basic ordinance was construed by the Supreme Court in taxi cab cases.","start":1038.556,"stop":1044.905,"duration":6.35},{"text":"In the taxi cab cases, they provided for a -- a finding of public convenience and necessity just exactly as it's provided here for the terminal vehicles.","start":1044.905,"stop":1061.667,"duration":16.76},{"text":"But the terminal vehicles in this particular case are the terminal vehicles without a contractual arrangement with the railroad.","start":1061.667,"stop":1072.511,"duration":10.84},{"text":"It's -- it's purely a local transportation facility.","start":1072.511,"stop":1080.619,"duration":8.11}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Court of Appeals disagreed with you on that.","start":1080.619,"stop":1083.268,"duration":2.65}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, the Court -- the Court of Appeals said that it was -- the Court of Appeals said that the provision for terminal vehicles applied to transfer but that it was unconstitutional because of the restriction.","start":1083.268,"stop":1099.859,"duration":16.59}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"The transfer was a shuttle as an interstate service.","start":1099.859,"stop":1102.305,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it is a shuttle but that's not the definition.","start":1102.305,"stop":1106.221,"duration":3.92},{"text":"That is not the definition of the terminal vehicle now.","start":1106.221,"stop":1110.817,"duration":4.6},{"text":"Terminal vehicle is merely another local transportation facility.","start":1110.817,"stop":1117.935,"duration":7.12},{"text":"This Court in the U.S. versus Yellow Cab Company, distinguished between the local transportation and the interstate transportation in the -- in the case of Yellow Cab against -- United States against Yellow Cab, 332 U.S. 218.","start":1117.935,"stop":1148.053,"duration":30.12},{"text":"The -- but I'm -- I'll come to that because what the Court did was to construe the ordinance in the light of what was said at a committee meeting of the city council.","start":1148.053,"stop":1164.666,"duration":16.61},{"text":"And I want -- I think that's a very important thing that I want to come to.","start":1164.666,"stop":1170.82,"duration":6.15}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess now Mr. Grossman.","start":1170.82,"stop":1175.922,"duration":5.1}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument, Part 2: City of Chicago v. Atchison, Topeka & Santa Fe Railway Company - March 06, 1958 (103)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13501","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Grossman, you may continue.","start":0,"stop":8.226,"duration":8.23}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":8.226,"stop":12.925,"duration":4.7},{"text":"The question before this Court is whether the Commerce Clause of the Constitution, invoked by our respondents in defense of the right of transfer to operate motor vehicles for compensation in the City of Chicago without a license, should have been considered by the courts below before the exhaustion of state administrative and judicial remedies to determine whether the public convenience and necessity provisions of the 1955 ordinance are applicable to Transfer's operations.","start":12.925,"stop":52.156,"duration":39.23},{"text":"The Commerce Clause became the decisive issue in the Court of Appeals on the assumption that the standards for determining whether public convenience and necessity require additional terminal vehicle service, apply to Transfer's operation and were intended to grant Parmelee a monopoly of the use of the city streets for interstation transportation service.","start":52.156,"stop":88.439,"duration":36.28},{"text":"I refer to the opinion of the Court which is attached to the petition for -- petition for certiorari and on page 50 where the Court said, “We are convinced that those provisions that is in Section 28-31.1, which would, in effect, limit the number of terminal vehicle licenses to those held by Parmelee on July 26, 1955, and give Parmelee perpetual control thereof, constitute a designation of Parmelee by the counsel of the city, in lieu of Transfer, the instrumentality selected by the terminal lines rather than the exercise of the City's police power over traffic.","start":88.439,"stop":157.019,"duration":68.58},{"text":"In this critical aspect, the 1955 ordinance is invalid.","start":157.019,"stop":162.817,"duration":5.8},{"text":"If there were any doubt that this conclusion is correct, the legislative history of the ordinance dispels that doubt.","start":162.817,"stop":173.888,"duration":11.07}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I ask you a question at this point?","start":173.888,"stop":176.049,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":176.049,"stop":176.153,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I want to get myself focused.","start":176.153,"stop":179.087,"duration":2.93},{"text":"The effect of this ordinance, as I understand it, was on the one hand to make Parmelee eligible for an interstation license which it would not have been eligible -- which it would not have been eligible under the preceding ordinance.","start":179.087,"stop":196.838,"duration":17.75},{"text":"And in converse to require Transfer to obtain a license before it could operate under its contract with terminals, is that right?","start":196.838,"stop":207.986,"duration":11.15}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I could -- you have it turned around.","start":207.986,"stop":212.108,"duration":4.12},{"text":"The purpose of the new ordinance, the 1955 ordinance, which was an amendment of an old ordinance by which Parmelee did have a contract for the railroads to perform this interstation service in intrastate and interstate commerce.","start":212.108,"stop":232.758,"duration":20.65},{"text":"It was amended so that the Parmelee operation became a -- a local transportation service only.","start":232.758,"stop":243.254,"duration":10.5},{"text":"That is to carry passengers for cash fares from railroad stations or steamships dock to any place within the City of Chicago - within the central business district of the City of Chicago.","start":243.254,"stop":257.281,"duration":14.03},{"text":"And the Transfer operation was by contract with the railroads exclusively for the transfer of passengers between stations, to carry railroad passengers between these stations while on a -- on a through route ticket and a thoroughfare ticket.","start":257.281,"stop":284.428,"duration":27.15}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But under the --","start":284.428,"stop":284.752,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Do I make myself clear?","start":284.752,"stop":285.553,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But under the old ordinance, the old ordinance --","start":285.553,"stop":288.403,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the old ordinance --","start":288.403,"stop":289.51,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Transfer would not have had to get a license from the city.","start":289.51,"stop":294.801,"duration":5.29}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"No.Under the old ordinance, Transfer -- Transfer couldn't get a license because railroad -- the railroads had an exclusive contract with Parmelee.","start":294.801,"stop":315.144,"duration":20.34},{"text":"They had an exclusive contract with Parmelee but the contract was not exclusively for the transfer of passengers.","start":315.144,"stop":324.423,"duration":9.28}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That was cancelled.","start":324.423,"stop":326.475,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"That was cancelled.","start":326.475,"stop":329.153,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me put it this way.","start":329.153,"stop":330.106,"duration":0.95},{"text":"I'm still confused.","start":330.106,"stop":332.644,"duration":2.54},{"text":"I thought under the old ordinance, a carrier that a company that was simply carrying interstation passengers was not subject to any city regulation under the old ordinance.","start":332.644,"stop":352.593,"duration":19.95}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, they were.","start":352.593,"stop":353.6,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"They were.","start":353.6,"stop":354.087,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Parmelee was under -- Parmelee was under the city regulation and had city licenses.","start":354.087,"stop":362.421,"duration":8.33}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And had a contract with the railroad.","start":362.421,"stop":363.97,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"And had a contract with the railroad.","start":363.97,"stop":365.107,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"So doing both?","start":365.107,"stop":366.888,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Doing -- doing both.","start":366.888,"stop":368.494,"duration":1.61},{"text":"Yes.","start":368.494,"stop":369.262,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Parmelee did both a transportation of -- of passengers between terminals --","start":369.262,"stop":378.348,"duration":9.09}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":378.348,"stop":378.981,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well as a local business to hotels.","start":378.981,"stop":381.4,"duration":2.42}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":381.4,"stop":383.505,"duration":2.11}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"And the amendment really consists of the elimination of the phrase “having a contract with the railroad”.","start":383.505,"stop":393.397,"duration":9.89}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":393.397,"stop":395.94,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Grossman, would it bother you to -- to give a short recital of the facts chronologically here so we could all -- all be oriented?","start":395.94,"stop":406.065,"duration":10.13},{"text":"I think it's obvious that we're -- that we're not quite oriented on the facts.","start":406.065,"stop":411.318,"duration":5.25}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":411.318,"stop":414.554,"duration":3.24},{"text":"Yesterday, I attempted to describe the operations of terminal vehicles by Parmelee from railroad terminal to any destination in the central business district of Chicago pursuant through licenses under a city ordinance before and after amendment in July 1955.","start":414.554,"stop":438.439,"duration":23.89},{"text":"Passengers were accepted by Parmelee for such transportation indiscriminately upon surrender of a coupon issued by a railroad for transfer between terminals or upon payment of the cash fare without identification as railroad passengers.","start":438.439,"stop":458.796,"duration":20.36},{"text":"Since Transfer was substituted for Parmelee under the contracts with the railroads, exclusively for the transfer of railroad passengers between terminal stations on through route tickets or coupons.","start":458.796,"stop":473.725,"duration":14.93},{"text":"Transfer commenced operations under its contracts without application for a license.","start":473.725,"stop":490.449,"duration":16.72},{"text":"That was -- that's the situation as it is today.","start":490.449,"stop":496.994,"duration":6.55},{"text":"Now, the power of the City to exercise its local police powers in the regulation of Transfer's operations is conceded by all concerned.","start":496.994,"stop":511.384,"duration":14.39},{"text":"And in the opinion of the Court of Appeals on page 52 of the petition for certiorari is a quotation from the opinion of the Court of Appeals where the Court of Appeals said, “Highways, being public property, users of them, although engaged exclusively in interstate commerce, are subject to regulation by the State or municipality to ensure safety and convenience, and the conservation of the highways.\"","start":511.384,"stop":553.091,"duration":41.71},{"text":"Now, the Court relied upon the history of the legislation to show that what the intention of the City Council was, was to grant to Parmelee a perpetual and exclusive right to perform the service which Transfer is now performing without a license.","start":553.091,"stop":588.187,"duration":35.1},{"text":"And the facts are, however, the referent part was to proceedings before the committee of the City Council at the time the ordinance was introduced.","start":588.187,"stop":605.958,"duration":17.77},{"text":"On page 90 to 92 is a correct transcript of the proceedings by court reporters as to what happened at the time of the introduction of an ordinance which originally was a grant or a franchise -- a special franchise to Parmelee, exclusively for the transfer of passengers to and from terminal stations, that's on page 85, and exclusive permission and authority was granted for a period of 10 years.","start":605.958,"stop":650.729,"duration":44.77},{"text":"Now, I went before the Committee and my remarks were misinterpreted, I think, by the Court of Appeals and by the clerk who took the minutes of the meeting down.","start":650.729,"stop":666.083,"duration":15.35},{"text":"I said that the ordinance, that is the franchise ordinance, was presented to me for consideration and I examined it very carefully, and that I don't think that it is within the corporate power of the City of Chicago, but that the objective could be obtained in some other way.","start":666.083,"stop":689.824,"duration":23.74},{"text":"Now then later on on page 92, the questions were asked by some of the older men, one of them -- one question was, “Do I understand that terminal vehicles embrace those vehicles that operate between railroad stations?”","start":689.824,"stop":710.264,"duration":20.44},{"text":"The Chairman said, “Yes.”","start":710.264,"stop":712.423,"duration":2.16},{"text":"But I said, “No, it is not.”","start":712.423,"stop":715.217,"duration":2.79},{"text":"The operation from railroad stations to points within the central business district, which is defined as the area bounded on the north by Ohio Street, and on the south by Roosevelt Road, and the Lake on the east, and Canal Street on the west, is in the railroad terminal area but it isn't necessarily between railroad stations.","start":715.217,"stop":737.847,"duration":22.63},{"text":"It may go from railroad stations to hotels and from hotels to railroad stations.","start":737.847,"stop":743.31,"duration":5.46},{"text":"That is the operation and that operation can be continued by amendments to the present ordinance without conflicting with any of the statutory provisions.","start":743.31,"stop":756.702,"duration":13.39},{"text":"Now, the purpose of the amendment which I drafted as a substitute for the franchise ordinance was an annual license fee to permit them to operate as a local transportation facility only.","start":756.702,"stop":773.616,"duration":16.91},{"text":"And that operation was what was in -- what was -- what the ordinance that was drafted as a substitute for the franchise ordinance was intended.","start":773.616,"stop":789.13,"duration":15.51},{"text":"I don't know whether I said --","start":789.13,"stop":794.792,"duration":5.66}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"When you say to permit “them” to operate, whom do you mean?","start":794.792,"stop":798.155,"duration":3.36},{"text":"Transfer?","start":798.155,"stop":799.152,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Parmelee.","start":799.152,"stop":800.172,"duration":1.02},{"text":"To permit them to operate only at a local transportation facility.","start":800.172,"stop":805.982,"duration":5.81}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That is not --","start":805.982,"stop":806.294,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Same as taxicabs.","start":806.294,"stop":808.554,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Not between terminals necessarily.","start":808.554,"stop":810.905,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Not necessarily between terminals and between terminals on a cash basis.","start":810.905,"stop":817.162,"duration":6.26},{"text":"In other words, the -- the passenger in the -- in the Parmelee vehicle would direct the Parmelee driver where he wants to go.","start":817.162,"stop":830.75,"duration":13.59},{"text":"He'd pay him a cash fare.","start":830.75,"stop":832.664,"duration":1.91},{"text":"If he wanted to go to another station, it was his choice.","start":832.664,"stop":835.819,"duration":3.15},{"text":"He could have selected a Parmelee vehicle.","start":835.819,"stop":838.583,"duration":2.76},{"text":"He could have selected -- he could have selected a taxicab or a street car or any other available vehicle to make either the transfer or to go to a hotel or any other place in which the passenger directed him to go.","start":838.583,"stop":857.172,"duration":18.59}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What happened to Parmelee's pay ride or his coupon?","start":857.172,"stop":861.147,"duration":3.98},{"text":"Could he use that in Parmelee?","start":861.147,"stop":863.759,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"He used -- they -- if there was a coupon prior to the amendment of 1955, I think that the coupon was accepted by Parmelee either to transfer him to a station or transfer him to a hotel.","start":863.759,"stop":887.576,"duration":23.82}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And after the new ordinance, then what?","start":887.576,"stop":889.672,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"After the new ordinance, he had no such things.","start":889.672,"stop":892.061,"duration":2.39},{"text":"They had no coupons.","start":892.061,"stop":893.332,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The coupon was -- would that be good with Transfer?","start":893.332,"stop":896.51,"duration":3.18}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"The coupon -- the coupon would be good for Transfer?","start":896.51,"stop":899.836,"duration":3.33},{"text":"Yes.","start":899.836,"stop":901.006,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But not for Parmelee.","start":901.006,"stop":901.99,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Not for Parmelee.","start":901.99,"stop":903.64,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Grossman, may I ask you, please?","start":903.64,"stop":907.549,"duration":3.91},{"text":"Are we here concerned now with what Parmelee may do?","start":907.549,"stop":913.043,"duration":5.49},{"text":"Are we not now concerned with what Transfer may do?","start":913.043,"stop":918.296,"duration":5.25},{"text":"Isn't that what's involved in this case?","start":918.296,"stop":919.162,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that's what involved.","start":919.162,"stop":921.731,"duration":2.57},{"text":"That's what's involved.","start":921.731,"stop":922.947,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- you contend, as I understand now, maybe I do not correctly understand, that Chicago has the right to refuse a license to Transfer to conduct as a carrier between these terminals interstate commerce.","start":922.947,"stop":947.301,"duration":24.35}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I do not say that.","start":947.301,"stop":948.939,"duration":1.64},{"text":"I say that Chicago has no right to refuse a license if a license were applied or if they are subject to the ordinance, they -- the license should be issued.","start":948.939,"stop":963.753,"duration":14.81},{"text":"The question is, are they subject to the ordinance?","start":963.753,"stop":967.424,"duration":3.67},{"text":"It's a question of the construction of the ordinance and not -- there's no constitutional question involved.","start":967.424,"stop":973.538,"duration":6.11}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":973.538,"stop":974.036,"duration":0.5},{"text":"Assume that they are subject to the ordinance, then, does not the ordinance say that before the license can be issued, Chicago must find public convenience and necessity?","start":974.036,"stop":988.877,"duration":14.84}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":988.877,"stop":989.293,"duration":0.42},{"text":"The -- that part of the ordinance of public convenience and necessity is strictly applicable to a local transportation facility.","start":989.293,"stop":998.764,"duration":9.47},{"text":"It cannot be applied to an operation which is exclusively in the interstate commerce on a through ticket.","start":998.764,"stop":1009.994,"duration":11.23}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't that all --","start":1009.994,"stop":1010.645,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"And that was the intention of that -- of that provision.","start":1010.645,"stop":1014.113,"duration":3.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Aren't you urging that we don't know what the ordinance requires?","start":1014.113,"stop":1018.618,"duration":4.5}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm --","start":1018.618,"stop":1018.808,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"How can you be so sure in telling us what it does require?","start":1018.808,"stop":1022.362,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Because it's the -- it's the same kind of a provision which is applicable to taxicabs in the City of Chicago.","start":1022.362,"stop":1032.666,"duration":10.3},{"text":"And when this Court said that in the case of U.S. versus Yellow Cab Company, when the Supreme Court said that the Parmelee operation was subject to the Sherman Act to the trust -- Antitrust Act because it was in the interstate commerce, but the Yellow Cab Companies were not, because the passengers had a choice.","start":1032.666,"stop":1060.582,"duration":27.92},{"text":"It was just -- it was just a local transportation.","start":1060.582,"stop":1064.962,"duration":4.38},{"text":"In the same case in that, U.S. against Yellow Cab Company, when the ordinance was passed to make Parmelee an operator the same as the Yellow Cab except with this limitation that they -- they could operate only within the central business district whereas, the Yellow Cab Company could operate throughout the City of Chicago.","start":1064.962,"stop":1093.876,"duration":28.91},{"text":"The -- it was -- it became necessary to limit the operations by this provision for determining whether public convenience and necessity required the additional service, the additional local service, I say, or whether the traffic conditions would permit additional service of the kind and character applied for.","start":1093.876,"stop":1125.45,"duration":31.57},{"text":"And I say that that 28-31, public convenience and necessity provision is applicable, it must be construed -- it must be construed as constitutional, if possible.","start":1125.45,"stop":1143.341,"duration":17.89},{"text":"And I say that for the state court to determine -- the state court should determine -- the state court should determine whether the provision limiting the number of vehicles to be operated in interstation service should -- is applicable in the light of any constitutional question which may be raised.","start":1143.341,"stop":1170.273,"duration":26.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Didn't I understand you to urge that the federal -- the federal courts have no business to strike down, if unconstitutional, an ordinance or any other act of legislation of a state if there is any doubt about a construction being given to it or has not yet been given to it by state court.","start":1170.273,"stop":1192.646,"duration":22.37}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Certain --","start":1192.646,"stop":1192.886,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And therefore suggesting that --","start":1192.886,"stop":1195.631,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"I think --","start":1195.631,"stop":1195.725,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- we better stick to that and not know what a construction is.","start":1195.725,"stop":1198.583,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I think, Your Honor, stated it more clearly than I probably could.","start":1198.583,"stop":1204.958,"duration":6.38},{"text":"That's -- that's the entire case.","start":1204.958,"stop":1208.013,"duration":3.05},{"text":"I've said -- I've -- I tried to say that and perhaps I was -- I haven't been --","start":1208.013,"stop":1216.964,"duration":8.95}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You didn't --","start":1216.964,"stop":1217.393,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"-- as clear as I should have been.","start":1217.393,"stop":1221.42,"duration":4.03}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not sure that does it follow because an enterprise is subject to the Sherman law as being within the requirement of interstate commerce under the Sherman law that therefore, the State is wholly supplanted in making any regulations and other relation?","start":1221.42,"stop":1242.06,"duration":20.64}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't --","start":1242.06,"stop":1242.538,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Any equation between amenability to the Sherman law in exclusion of state action?","start":1242.538,"stop":1248.041,"duration":5.5}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't --","start":1248.041,"stop":1248.229,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I haven't thought so.","start":1248.229,"stop":1249.395,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't -- I don't think (Voice Overlap) -- I don't think that it goes that far, yet.","start":1249.395,"stop":1254.179,"duration":4.78},{"text":"I think -- I think Your Honor is right that the facts that they are subject to criminal prosecution under the antitrust laws and the operation is partly in interstate commerce.It doesn't follow that the operation is not subject to license by the City.","start":1254.179,"stop":1283.481,"duration":29.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I'm not saying it is.","start":1283.481,"stop":1284.42,"duration":0.94},{"text":"All I'm saying is it doesn't follow.","start":1284.42,"stop":1286.302,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"It doesn't follow.","start":1286.302,"stop":1287.215,"duration":0.91},{"text":"Yes, that's right.","start":1287.215,"stop":1287.831,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The Sherman law excludes the State from action.","start":1287.831,"stop":1290.497,"duration":2.67},{"text":"It certainly doesn't exclude this from taxation.","start":1290.497,"stop":1293.42,"duration":2.92},{"text":"How do I know whether it's excluded on that if that isn't a -- an absolute proposition of law?","start":1293.42,"stop":1298.26,"duration":4.84}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"This is purely regulation.","start":1298.26,"stop":1301.612,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Grossman, may I bother you once more, please?","start":1301.612,"stop":1305.348,"duration":3.74}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly.","start":1305.348,"stop":1306.199,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Did the Court of Appeals hold that Chicago couldn't require a license from Transfer?","start":1306.199,"stop":1314.908,"duration":8.71}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1314.908,"stop":1315.773,"duration":0.87},{"text":"It held the ordinance for it.","start":1315.773,"stop":1318.166,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it held that void only in that it -- you could not require it to apply for a certificate of convenience and necessity, isn't that right?","start":1318.166,"stop":1329.909,"duration":11.74}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1329.909,"stop":1330.13,"duration":0.22},{"text":"It --","start":1330.13,"stop":1330.163,"duration":0.03}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"But did -- didn't Judge Schnackenberg say that Chicago still had the right under its police powers to require a license?","start":1330.163,"stop":1337.208,"duration":7.05}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":1337.208,"stop":1338.583,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"But he's merely held, did he not, as I understood the opinion, that you have no right to require the Transfer Company to apply for -- and go through the proceedings to obtain a certificate of convenience and necessity which they probably couldn't get.","start":1338.583,"stop":1358.962,"duration":20.38}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1358.962,"stop":1359.392,"duration":0.43},{"text":"Well we have -- he held that we have no right to require it of Transfer Company.","start":1359.392,"stop":1367.097,"duration":7.7}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1367.097,"stop":1367.695,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"But we certainly have a right to require it and there is no reason why that section should have been held void, we have a right to require it of operators like Parmelee --","start":1367.695,"stop":1383.135,"duration":15.44}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"To do --","start":1383.135,"stop":1383.336,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of local --","start":1383.336,"stop":1384.215,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"To do a local business.","start":1384.215,"stop":1385.085,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"To do a local business.","start":1385.085,"stop":1386.086,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"But what about requiring it or denying it to one who is engaged exclusively in commerce?","start":1386.086,"stop":1392.046,"duration":5.96}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree that the ordinance does not -- that that provision of the ordinance, that section of the ordinance which Judge Schnackenberg held invalid and therefore held invalid all of the amendments in 1955, does not apply to Transfer operations.","start":1392.046,"stop":1415.747,"duration":23.7}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Will isn't on this (Voice Overlap)?","start":1415.747,"stop":1415.954,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"The Transfer operations are still -- may still be subject to license.","start":1415.954,"stop":1421.194,"duration":5.24}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Didn't he say that?","start":1421.194,"stop":1421.968,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"He said that.","start":1421.968,"stop":1422.908,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"In that --","start":1422.908,"stop":1423.739,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"He said that, but he said that it's -- it's subject to license under the old ordinance and he nullified the 1955 ordinance because of the -- of the provision, because of the provision that --","start":1423.739,"stop":1445.658,"duration":21.92}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Chicago had no right to require them to obtain a certificate --","start":1445.658,"stop":1449.571,"duration":3.91}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1449.571,"stop":1449.949,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of convenience and necessity which they couldn't get.","start":1449.949,"stop":1452.264,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1452.264,"stop":1452.714,"duration":0.45},{"text":"That's right.","start":1452.714,"stop":1453.812,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that all he said?","start":1453.812,"stop":1455.87,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, he said a whole lot more than that.","start":1455.87,"stop":1458.397,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what he decided, isn't it?","start":1458.397,"stop":1459.65,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that's what he cited.","start":1459.65,"stop":1461.247,"duration":1.6},{"text":"The question -- and I say that the -- that the constitutional question is not in -- was not involved.","start":1461.247,"stop":1467.658,"duration":6.41},{"text":"It shouldn't have been involved.","start":1467.658,"stop":1470.823,"duration":3.17},{"text":"The sole question here and the -- and this respondent submitted the question.","start":1470.823,"stop":1476.228,"duration":5.4},{"text":"First, that the ordinance does not apply -- that the 1955 ordinance does not apply to Transfer.","start":1476.228,"stop":1483.819,"duration":7.59},{"text":"They contended that.","start":1483.819,"stop":1485.363,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And you agree with that?","start":1485.363,"stop":1485.683,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"And they said --","start":1485.683,"stop":1486.632,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And you agree with it?","start":1486.632,"stop":1487.533,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree with it.","start":1487.533,"stop":1488.724,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1488.724,"stop":1490.14,"duration":1.42},{"text":"Now, go on from there.","start":1490.14,"stop":1491.368,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"And from there -- from there I say that -- that the judgment of the appellate court, the Court of Appeals in striking down the ordinance of 1955, because the public convenience and necessity provision is invalid which it is not, as applied to Parmelee or applied to any operator.","start":1491.368,"stop":1526.6,"duration":35.23}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"How about as applied to Transfer?","start":1526.6,"stop":1529.662,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"I say that it is -- it wasn't -- it does not apply to Transfer and that therefore, the ordinance should not have been held invalid --","start":1529.662,"stop":1542.288,"duration":12.63}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Is Transfer here --","start":1542.288,"stop":1542.504,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and there should have been no constitutional question --","start":1542.504,"stop":1545.825,"duration":3.32}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Is --","start":1545.825,"stop":1545.967,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"-- as to whether that -- as to whether that provision of public convenience and necessity applies to Transfer is a question, I think, which is out of the case.","start":1545.967,"stop":1559.647,"duration":13.68}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is Transfer before us?","start":1559.647,"stop":1561.657,"duration":2.01},{"text":"Is Transfer --","start":1561.657,"stop":1562.343,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly it is.","start":1562.343,"stop":1566.335,"duration":3.99},{"text":"Transfer is a party.","start":1566.335,"stop":1568.168,"duration":1.83},{"text":"And they claimed that the ordinance doesn't apply to them.","start":1568.168,"stop":1572.003,"duration":3.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And you agree to that?","start":1572.003,"stop":1572.172,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"The District Court said --","start":1572.172,"stop":1573.73,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And you agree to that.","start":1573.73,"stop":1575.255,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"I personally agree with that.","start":1575.255,"stop":1577.185,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know -- I don't know what that means personally if the City of Chicago --","start":1577.185,"stop":1580.819,"duration":3.63}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"The City of Chicago takes a position that 28 at the Section 31-1 of the public convenience and necessity section applies to all local operations between railroad stations and any destination in the central business district of the City.","start":1580.819,"stop":1606.963,"duration":26.14}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Including --","start":1606.963,"stop":1608.106,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Not including --","start":1608.106,"stop":1608.592,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Transfer.","start":1608.592,"stop":1609.951,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Inclu -- including those that are not under contract for interstation transfer including those who do not travel on railroads on a through ticket.","start":1609.951,"stop":1626.051,"duration":16.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Grossman, can you -- can we be clear about this thing because I'm not clear?","start":1626.051,"stop":1632.56,"duration":6.51},{"text":"This involved the lower court struck down an ordinance of 1955.","start":1632.56,"stop":1636.462,"duration":3.9}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1636.462,"stop":1639.073,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Transfer says it isn't within the ordinance and you agree to that, do you?","start":1639.073,"stop":1647.168,"duration":8.09}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Transfer is --","start":1647.168,"stop":1647.274,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I think you said it is.","start":1647.274,"stop":1648.382,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Transfer is not within that ordinance.","start":1648.382,"stop":1650.792,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1650.792,"stop":1651.524,"duration":0.73},{"text":"Then I do not understand that there's a litigation before the Court but if Transfer claims a right which you recognize, what is the contest as between Chicago and Transfer?","start":1651.524,"stop":1662.217,"duration":10.69}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"The question is to whether Transfer should be licensed.","start":1662.217,"stop":1667.112,"duration":4.89},{"text":"Should have applied for a license and the --","start":1667.112,"stop":1671.942,"duration":4.83}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Then that has nothing to do with 1955, does it?","start":1671.942,"stop":1674.625,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"That has nothing to do with the 1955 ordinance.","start":1674.625,"stop":1677.467,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1677.467,"stop":1679.149,"duration":1.68},{"text":"In your view.","start":1679.149,"stop":1681.78,"duration":2.63},{"text":"And is that the ordinance before us or there's some other ordinance?","start":1681.78,"stop":1683.897,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the ordinance before you.","start":1683.897,"stop":1685.367,"duration":1.47},{"text":"It was struck down.","start":1685.367,"stop":1686.292,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well it's struck down but the other ordinance, is that before us too?","start":1686.292,"stop":1690.327,"duration":4.04}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"The other ordinance, say -- this wasn't a mandatory ordinance, the other ordinance is -- the other ordinance is applicable if this ordinance is -- if this ordinance is invalid.","start":1690.327,"stop":1706.12,"duration":15.79},{"text":"That is the other ordinance still has provision for licensing public passenger vehicles.","start":1706.12,"stop":1715.114,"duration":8.99},{"text":"And so, does the 1955 ordinance have provision for -- the question -- the question maybe put this way.","start":1715.114,"stop":1725.703,"duration":10.59},{"text":"It's claimed on one side that a terminal vehicle is -- that the definition of a terminal vehicle doesn't apply to Transfer.","start":1725.703,"stop":1737.748,"duration":12.05},{"text":"On the other side, in the case -- Parmelee, who was an intervener, claims that terminal -- the definition of terminal vehicle is broad enough to include Transfer.","start":1737.748,"stop":1751.585,"duration":13.84},{"text":"The contest was between these two companies.","start":1751.585,"stop":1753.924,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But that isn't the case you're arguing, is it?","start":1753.924,"stop":1756.216,"duration":2.29}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"I am -- I am -- yes, I'm arguing -- I'm arguing this case.","start":1756.216,"stop":1762.823,"duration":6.61},{"text":"I say that so far as public convenience and necessity are concerned, it is not applicable.","start":1762.823,"stop":1770.796,"duration":7.97},{"text":"This provision of the 1955 ordinance is -- is inapplicable to Transfer.","start":1770.796,"stop":1777.557,"duration":6.76},{"text":"But I say that the question of whether they are entitled to a license, whether they -- whether the ordinance provides for the licensing of Transfer vehicles, is one for the state courts to determine.","start":1777.557,"stop":1797.144,"duration":19.59}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did -- did the Court of Appeals pass on that question?","start":1797.144,"stop":1799.889,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it did not.","start":1799.889,"stop":1801.388,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So that --","start":1801.388,"stop":1801.541,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"It assumed that they were not -- that they didn't have to have a license.","start":1801.541,"stop":1806.621,"duration":5.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So as I understand it, Transfer -- the position of Transfer under the 1955 Act is not a matter of controversy between you and Transfer, is that right?","start":1806.621,"stop":1820.753,"duration":14.13}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"It isn't that.","start":1820.753,"stop":1821.029,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And whatever other rights they may have, the lower court didn't pass on it.","start":1821.029,"stop":1824.477,"duration":3.45},{"text":"Is that right?","start":1824.477,"stop":1825.373,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"The lower court said they didn't have to apply for a license because the 1955 ordinance was void.","start":1825.373,"stop":1832.235,"duration":6.86},{"text":"Void because Section 28-31.1 was invalid as an interference with interstate commerce.","start":1832.235,"stop":1841.792,"duration":9.56},{"text":"Now, I say that 28-31.1 is not invalid because it's applicable to local transportation and that the rest of the ordinance of 1955 is valid as applied to Transfer and as applied to -- to Parmelee if it is the terminal vehicle.","start":1841.792,"stop":1872.498,"duration":30.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as I understand you and you please correct me because I can assure you my head is foggy on this subject.","start":1872.498,"stop":1878.26,"duration":5.76},{"text":"As I understand you, the Court invalidated an ordinance because it couldn't be made applicable to transportation companies engaged in interstate commerce and you agree with that, that the ordinance doesn't apply to that.","start":1878.26,"stop":1892.955,"duration":14.69},{"text":"Is that right?","start":1892.955,"stop":1893.723,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I didn't say I agree with that.","start":1893.723,"stop":1896.344,"duration":2.62},{"text":"I --","start":1896.344,"stop":1896.404,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought you said --","start":1896.404,"stop":1896.894,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"I --","start":1896.894,"stop":1897.187,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the ordinance --","start":1897.187,"stop":1897.53,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"I --","start":1897.53,"stop":1897.923,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- is a matter of construction.","start":1897.923,"stop":1899.815,"duration":1.89},{"text":"It doesn't apply to Transfer.","start":1899.815,"stop":1901.218,"duration":1.4},{"text":"Is that right?","start":1901.218,"stop":1902.287,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I agree that the provision requiring a determination of public convenience and necessity does not apply to Transfer.","start":1902.287,"stop":1914.299,"duration":12.01},{"text":"That's all I agreed to.","start":1914.299,"stop":1916.19,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Because it is engaged in commerce.","start":1916.19,"stop":1917.896,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Because it is engaged ‘exclusively' --","start":1917.896,"stop":1922.993,"duration":5.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In commerce.","start":1922.993,"stop":1923.998,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in interstate commerce.","start":1923.998,"stop":1925.48,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And that is the ground on which the Court of Appeals found it invalid that it couldn't apply --","start":1925.48,"stop":1931.355,"duration":5.88}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the ground that have --","start":1931.355,"stop":1932.592,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that right?","start":1932.592,"stop":1934.698,"duration":2.11}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"It didn't find it invalid merely as to Transfer --","start":1934.698,"stop":1939.32,"duration":4.62}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm talking about Transfer for the moment just stick to that.","start":1939.32,"stop":1941.104,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm -- it didn't -- it -- it found the whole 1955 ordinance --","start":1941.104,"stop":1946.093,"duration":4.99}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I understand that.","start":1946.093,"stop":1947.256,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"-- invalid.","start":1947.256,"stop":1947.4,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1947.4,"stop":1948.137,"duration":0.74},{"text":"But so as far as Transfer is concerned, insofar as the invalidation was rested on the engaging in interstate commerce, you say the ordinance doesn't apply to Transfer, is that right?","start":1948.137,"stop":1960.639,"duration":12.5}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"I say that section of the ordinance doesn't apply.","start":1960.639,"stop":1962.496,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1962.496,"stop":1964.378,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"But the -- I -- I say there is -- they may still be required to secure a license in that.","start":1964.378,"stop":1974.818,"duration":10.44}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Under some other -- under the prior ordinance.","start":1974.818,"stop":1976.696,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, under this ordinance because this ordinance provides, let me -- let me read it to you.","start":1976.696,"stop":1984.504,"duration":7.81}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is it, Mr. Grossman, so we can follow this?","start":1984.504,"stop":1988.318,"duration":3.81}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"It's on page --","start":1988.318,"stop":1994.606,"duration":6.29}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The court below knocked out the whole ordinance, did it?","start":1994.606,"stop":1997.226,"duration":2.62},{"text":"The entire ordinance, Mr. Grossman?","start":1997.226,"stop":1998.486,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"The entire ordinance.","start":1998.486,"stop":1999.828,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And the -- you agree that the -- insofar as invalidation was rested on interstate commerce, that was a gratuitous thing because the ordinance doesn't apply to that.","start":1999.828,"stop":2010.12,"duration":10.29}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2010.12,"stop":2011.227,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now which section is knocked out for grounds other than commerce?","start":2011.227,"stop":2025.427,"duration":14.2}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'll read it from my -- from my note because I have it here.","start":2025.427,"stop":2030.756,"duration":5.33},{"text":"Here is what the ordinance -- the amendatory ordinance was.","start":2030.756,"stop":2033.556,"duration":2.8},{"text":"“Be it ordained by the City Council, Section 1.","start":2033.556,"stop":2036.201,"duration":2.64},{"text":"Section 28, one of the Municipal Court of Chicago has amended by striking the definition of terminal vehicle contained therein and substituting therefore the following -","start":2036.201,"stop":2046.013,"duration":9.81},{"text":"Terminal vehicle means a public passenger vehicle which is operated exclusively for the transportation of passengers from railroad terminal stations, and steamship docks, the points within the area defined in Section 28-31.","start":2046.013,"stop":2062.398,"duration":16.39},{"text":"And terminal vehicle shall not be used for transportation of passengers for hire except from railroad terminal stations and steamship docks to destinations in the central business area of the City.”","start":2062.398,"stop":2076.69,"duration":14.29},{"text":"Now then comes the section with reference to public convenience and necessity and the section relating to local fares.","start":2076.69,"stop":2087.216,"duration":10.53},{"text":"I think that that's -- I had it a moment ago, but I lost the 40 -- I think it is 42, isn't it?","start":2087.216,"stop":2099.124,"duration":11.91},{"text":"Yes.","start":2099.124,"stop":2099.975,"duration":0.85},{"text":"It's Exhibit B on page 44 of the transcript.","start":2099.975,"stop":2107.41,"duration":7.43},{"text":"Now, the provisions of the ordinance which are not amended and which I say is a question for the administrative and judicial departments of the State of Illinois to determine, is that that section which remains at Section 28-2, “It is unlawful for any person other than a metropolitan transit authority or public utility to operate any vehicle or for any such person who is the owner of any vehicle to permit it to be operated on any public way for the transportation of passengers for hire from place to place within the corporate limits of the city except on a funeral trip, unless it is licensed by the city as a public passenger vehicle.”","start":2107.41,"stop":2170.901,"duration":63.49},{"text":"Now, that is on page -- that's in the record on page 173 which I read yesterday, page 173 of the record.","start":2170.901,"stop":2195.776,"duration":24.88},{"text":"So that the question whether they're engaged in -- even though that -- even though it's in the interstate commerce.","start":2195.776,"stop":2206.654,"duration":10.88},{"text":"They are engaged in transporting persons between stations, between two points within the City, within the corporate limits of the City.","start":2206.654,"stop":2216.755,"duration":10.1},{"text":"And the -- Judge Schnackenberg said in his -- in his opinion which I read before at the -- in the early part of the day.","start":2216.755,"stop":2233.524,"duration":16.77},{"text":"That the City has a right to license the operation even though it is an interstate commerce.","start":2233.524,"stop":2241.165,"duration":7.64},{"text":"And it's been so held even though it's an interstate commerce.","start":2241.165,"stop":2246.044,"duration":4.88},{"text":"The City has the right to require a license and to regulate it under its police power.","start":2246.044,"stop":2251.274,"duration":5.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the “but”?","start":2251.274,"stop":2253.313,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"But the City has no right to limit or to deny a license to Parmelee simply because of economic -- the economic grounds, that is limit the number of vehicles to those that are necessary for the service.","start":2253.313,"stop":2280.713,"duration":27.4},{"text":"That's the public convenience and necessity provision.","start":2280.713,"stop":2286.527,"duration":5.81}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And you say that that was really not an issue before the federal court because the ordinance either doesn't -- or the existing legal authority of Chicago either doesn't or we don't know whether it does give monopoly power?","start":2286.527,"stop":2308.322,"duration":21.8},{"text":"Is that what you're saying?","start":2308.322,"stop":2309.155,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"It doesn't give monopoly power.","start":2309.155,"stop":2311.94,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what you're saying.","start":2311.94,"stop":2313.204,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"It's been so held under the state court in the taxicab cases.","start":2313.204,"stop":2317.077,"duration":3.87}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But haven't you just said that that's the reason why Judge Schnackenberg wrote the way he wrote?","start":2317.077,"stop":2321.694,"duration":4.62}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2321.694,"stop":2322.115,"duration":0.42},{"text":"Judge Schnackenberg said that it was invalid because there was an interference with interstate commerce.","start":2322.115,"stop":2328.021,"duration":5.91},{"text":"But it's not --","start":2328.021,"stop":2329.496,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I give up.","start":2329.496,"stop":2329.756,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the monopoly.","start":2329.756,"stop":2330.695,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I give up but you've said that that isn't the contention that you are making.","start":2330.695,"stop":2333.827,"duration":3.13},{"text":"You're admitting that.","start":2333.827,"stop":2334.845,"duration":1.02},{"text":"And if it's interstate commerce --","start":2334.845,"stop":2335.216,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm admitting that.","start":2335.216,"stop":2336.557,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it's not covered.","start":2336.557,"stop":2337.865,"duration":1.31},{"text":"But you say, nevertheless, the City, for reasons of policing the traffic conditions in the second, if it is the second largest City in the United States, I don't know but Los Angeles is creeping up on this, that for police reasons, it may regulate to make life possible in the City of Chicago.","start":2337.865,"stop":2357.496,"duration":19.63}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":2357.496,"stop":2367.958,"duration":10.46},{"text":"I don't think there's anything more that I need to say upon this.","start":2367.958,"stop":2372.074,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":2372.074,"stop":2374.818,"duration":2.74},{"text":"Mr. Mathews.","start":2374.818,"stop":2393.158,"duration":18.34}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":2393.158,"stop":2399.119,"duration":5.96},{"text":"I want if I may to make a complete statement of the facts in this case.","start":2399.119,"stop":2408.594,"duration":9.47},{"text":"First of all, however, because the subject has been a matter of colloquy for the past 15 or 20 minutes, I want to correct one thing.","start":2408.594,"stop":2423.091,"duration":14.5},{"text":"Of course, I do not know the extent to which Mr. Grossman is now authorized to speak for the City Council of the City of Chicago.","start":2423.091,"stop":2436.08,"duration":12.99},{"text":"But in both courts below, the City of Chicago and Mr. Grossman by signed pleadings and representations of attorneys and counselors of the Court, took the firm position that the 1955 Public Convenience and Necessity Provision of the ordinance was applicable to the Transfer operation being carried on under the contract between Transfer and the railroads.","start":2436.08,"stop":2468.429,"duration":32.35}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Will you tell me, Mr. Mathews, in one sentence, what would be the practical effect of the application of the convenience and necessity provision?","start":2468.429,"stop":2479.934,"duration":11.51}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"The practical effect -- well, the -- you have to go a little bit farther than that.","start":2479.934,"stop":2484.67,"duration":4.74}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't want it -- I don't -- let me interrupt this confusing --","start":2484.67,"stop":2486.827,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I just as well -- just as well take that up at this time.","start":2486.827,"stop":2491.559,"duration":4.73},{"text":"Under the amendment of 1955, Transfer cannot operate any vehicle in the City of Chicago unless, first, it applies to the Commissioner of public vehicles.","start":2491.559,"stop":2506.522,"duration":14.96},{"text":"And the Commissioner after a hearing determines that public convenience and necessity requires the vehicles and then -- and here's the thing that for one reason or another, our adversaries don't say anything about, after the commissioner has made a finding, the City Council of the City of Chicago must pass an ordinance authorizing Transfer to operate any vehicle.","start":2506.522,"stop":2537.033,"duration":30.51},{"text":"In other words, this is not a case merely of application to an administrate for an administrative finding of public convenience and necessity or whatever else you want to call it.","start":2537.033,"stop":2549.166,"duration":12.13},{"text":"The administrator in effect, if we may borrow a terminology from the regulatory commissions, the administrator is made an examiner, say to use the terminology of the Interstate Commerce Act.","start":2549.166,"stop":2561.353,"duration":12.19},{"text":"And he makes a recommendation, but the recommendation is worth nothing unless the City Council of the City of Chicago passes an ordinance.","start":2561.353,"stop":2569.926,"duration":8.57},{"text":"Now, the City Council of the City of Chicago, if a subject is within its ordaining powers has power to -- thank you -- has power to pass an ordinance or to refrain from passing an ordinance.","start":2569.926,"stop":2590.374,"duration":20.45},{"text":"So under the 1955 Amendment, which Mr. Grossman himself by signed pleadings in the courts below in the City of Chicago by its corporation council, by signed pleadings in the courts below, has insisted stoutly applies to the Transfer operation here involved, we could not operate unless the City Council of the City of Chicago authorizes to do so by ordinance.","start":2590.374,"stop":2623.188,"duration":32.81},{"text":"Now, for example, devoting a little more time to this point than I thought I would at the beginning, but I -- I -- it's -- I can see its importance, of course.","start":2623.188,"stop":2636.255,"duration":13.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Would it interfere with both the answer you're making to Justice Brennan and your own argument if you would state briefly what the critical condition is with reference to these facilities of going from one station to another, what the existing situation was, what the ordinance did, what you object to in the ordinance?","start":2636.255,"stop":2658.837,"duration":22.58}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice, I -- I think I will proceed to that right now.","start":2658.837,"stop":2661.5,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I think if you get to the facts of (Voice Overlap) --","start":2661.5,"stop":2663.203,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I believe so.","start":2663.203,"stop":2663.814,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- could you tell us what the (Voice Overlap) --","start":2663.814,"stop":2664.861,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I merely -- I merely adverted to these other things because they were so surprising to me.","start":2664.861,"stop":2670.044,"duration":5.18},{"text":"Very well, I -- I think that's -- I think I shall proceed along that line.","start":2670.044,"stop":2677.058,"duration":7.01},{"text":"The 21 railroads having passenger -- operating passenger trains into Chicago and a corporation known as Railroad Transfer Service, Incorporated started an action in the United States District Court in Chicago for a declaratory judgment that an ordinance of the City of Chicago is inapplicable to them or if applicable, is violative of the Commerce Clause.","start":2677.058,"stop":2709.967,"duration":32.91},{"text":"The -- in the District Court there, upon representations of the City of Chicago, Mr. Grossman prepared a conclusion of law for the District Court, that the conclusion of law been to the effect that the public convenience and necessity provision applies to the Transfer operation.","start":2709.967,"stop":2733.197,"duration":23.23},{"text":"The District Court held the ordinance applicable in all respects to Transfer and held it valid.","start":2733.197,"stop":2742.316,"duration":9.12},{"text":"The railroads and Transfer appealed to the Court of Appeals.","start":2742.316,"stop":2747.648,"duration":5.33},{"text":"Now, the Court of Appeals held that the railroads are operating the interstation transfer service under Section 202 (c) (2) of the Interstate Commerce Act which is setout in full on pages 30 to 31 of our brief.","start":2747.648,"stop":2772.034,"duration":24.39},{"text":"I will go back to that Act more in detail after I've stated the general background.But the District Court -- I mean the Court of Appeals held that the -- that one section of the Chicago ordinance obstructed the interstate commerce being conducted by the railroads between the terminal stations under the authority of Section 202 (c) (2) of the Interstate Commerce Act.","start":2772.034,"stop":2809.407,"duration":37.37},{"text":"The Court of Appeals held every other section of the ordinance valid and applicable to the Transfer operation, and the railroads and Transfer did not appeal from any part of the judgment of the Court of Appeals.","start":2809.407,"stop":2827.266,"duration":17.86},{"text":"Now, that is what happened in the District Court and that in very brief capsule -- I mean, in both courts below and that in very brief capsule is -- was the Court proceeding.","start":2827.266,"stop":2839.882,"duration":12.62},{"text":"Now, I go back to the factual background but I will return, if time permits and I'm sure it will, to a comparison of the ordinance -- the conflicting ordinance and the section of the Interstate Commerce Act to which I refer.","start":2839.882,"stop":2858.46,"duration":18.58},{"text":"For many years, the 21 railroads operating passenger trains in Chicago have provided by tariffs filed with both the Interstate Commerce Commission and the Illinois Commerce Commission for the transfer of passengers between Chicago stations; that is of passengers travelling on through tickets.","start":2858.46,"stop":2883.282,"duration":24.82},{"text":"There are eight passenger terminals in downtown Chicago served by the 21 railroads.","start":2883.282,"stop":2890.444,"duration":7.16},{"text":"Each terminals serves from one to six railroads.","start":2890.444,"stop":2894.354,"duration":3.91},{"text":"Some through passengers -- well, no railroad, as you no doubt know, passes through Chicago but several thousand passengers per day travel on through railroad tickets through Chicago, that is from a point of origin outside Chicago on beyond the point of origin.","start":2894.354,"stop":2917.618,"duration":23.26},{"text":"The passenger buys at his point of origin a railroad ticket consisting of a series of coupons, good for each railroad on which he operates to destination.","start":2917.618,"stop":2928.554,"duration":10.94},{"text":"If the passenger in Chicago must transfer from an incoming railroad -- from the station of an incoming railroad to another station of the outgoing railroad, that is if they're not in the same station, that through ticket has a coupon.","start":2928.554,"stop":2945.752,"duration":17.2},{"text":"The passenger arrives in Chicago and he hands that coupon to a representative of the Transfer agency of the railroads and he and his baggage are carried to the outgoing railroad, where the price of the whole ticket is more than a very small minimum, it varies -- no -- no need to state that, but substantially -- in the case of substantially all tickets, that extra coupon does not add -- there's no charge for it at all over the regular tariff fare for the passenger ticket.","start":2945.752,"stop":2988.535,"duration":42.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It's part of the tariff ticket.","start":2988.535,"stop":2990.916,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- that's correct.","start":2990.916,"stop":2991.961,"duration":1.04},{"text":"I think that's fair to say, except this, and I want to make this point plain.","start":2991.961,"stop":2997.17,"duration":5.21},{"text":"Where the passenger does not have to change stations, where, for instance, he arrives in the union station and goes out of the union station, his ticket is the same price as the passenger who has Transfer.","start":2997.17,"stop":3007.563,"duration":10.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It's absorbed.","start":3007.563,"stop":3008.734,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3008.734,"stop":3009.988,"duration":1.25},{"text":"Now, the transfer agent obtains his pay or his compensation for performing this service from the outgoing railroad.","start":3009.988,"stop":3019.288,"duration":9.3},{"text":"That is the Transfer agent collects these coupons and at the end of the month or whatever the time is agreed upon, he sends a statement for all of the transfer coupons he's collected to the outgoing railroad and he's paid by them.","start":3019.288,"stop":3039.935,"duration":20.65},{"text":"Now, I want to call your attention, something that is I think of greatest importance at this point.","start":3039.935,"stop":3054.061,"duration":14.13},{"text":"This Transfer operation through passengers -- oh, I should give you a few statistics, I think.","start":3054.061,"stop":3062.486,"duration":8.42},{"text":"Approximately 3900 passengers per day on the average transfer in Chicago by means of this transfer service.","start":3062.486,"stop":3072.937,"duration":10.45},{"text":"That is from an incoming station to an outgoing station.","start":3072.937,"stop":3077.396,"duration":4.46},{"text":"And more than 99% of this 3900 are travelling between destinations located in different states.","start":3077.396,"stop":3085.925,"duration":8.53},{"text":"And in the Yellow Cab case in 322 U.S., this Court specifically held that that particular operation is interstate commerce.","start":3085.925,"stop":3093.888,"duration":7.96},{"text":"That is the transfer over the Chicago streets of a traveler travelling in interstate commerce.","start":3093.888,"stop":3101.174,"duration":7.29},{"text":"Now, this interstation transfer of passengers under the contract between Transfer and the railroads and under the former arrangement between Parmelee and the railroads is squarely within the authorization of Section 202 (c) (2) of the Interstate Commerce Act.","start":3101.174,"stop":3128.765,"duration":27.59},{"text":"As I said, that Section is setout in full on pages 30 and 31 of our brief, by paragraph (1) of Section 202 (c), transportation by motor vehicle, by carriers, by railroad, or water, or freight forwarders, when performed within the terminal areas of those carriers for transfer, collection, or delivery service are exempt from Part 2 of the Interstate Commerce Act, regulating motor carriers, but are made railroad transportation subject to Part 1.","start":3128.765,"stop":3177.851,"duration":49.09},{"text":"That -- this Section 202 (c) was enacted in 1940, an amendment in 1942 has nothing material to this controversy.","start":3177.851,"stop":3189.533,"duration":11.68},{"text":"However, subparagraph (2) of Section 202 (c) provides this, and I'm reading a few lines from the quote at page 31 of my brief, “Transportation by motor vehicle by any person whether as agent or under a contractual arrangement for a common carrier by railroad subject to Part 1.","start":3189.533,"stop":3217.774,"duration":28.24},{"text":"In the performance within terminal areas, the transfer, collection, or delivery service shall be considered to be performed by such carrier,” now that means carrier by railroad, “as part of and shall be regulated in the same manner as the transportation by railroad to which such services are incidental.","start":3217.774,"stop":3238.049,"duration":20.28},{"text":"Now, I want to go back now to the impact of the ordinance of the City of Chicago upon -- or the conflict ordinance of the City of Chicago upon this section, but I want to return to this section later on to point out the construction by the Interstate Commerce Commission and the construction of similar statutes by the courts.","start":3238.049,"stop":3261.906,"duration":23.86},{"text":"But -- and as I've said at the very beginning, the Court of Appeals held that the one section of the 1955 ordinance abstracted the interstate operation, transfer operation being conducted by the railroads under 202 (c) (2).","start":3261.906,"stop":3283.498,"duration":21.59}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3283.498,"stop":3286.496,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct, Your Honor.","start":3286.496,"stop":3287.501,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3287.501,"stop":3289.553,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3289.553,"stop":3291.1,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"And is that the one having to do with the convenience and necessity?","start":3291.1,"stop":3295.625,"duration":4.53}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the one, yes.","start":3295.625,"stop":3297.175,"duration":1.55},{"text":"That -- that is the one that the -- the -- the only provision of the entire ordinance that the Court of Appeals held invalid was the one that required the railroads to prove to the satisfaction of the City of Chicago and obtain an ordinance finding that public convenience and necessity requires this operation that is authorized by the Interstate Commerce Act.","start":3297.175,"stop":3322.341,"duration":25.17}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Did they hold it invalid as a violation of the Constitution or as a violation of the acts of Congress which you've just referred?","start":3322.341,"stop":3329.535,"duration":7.19}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"They're not specific on that but their language makes it clear that it is held a violation of the -- both the Commerce Clause and the Interstate Commerce Act.","start":3329.535,"stop":3345.705,"duration":16.17},{"text":"Now --","start":3345.705,"stop":3346.814,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3346.814,"stop":3357.445,"duration":10.63}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes.","start":3357.445,"stop":3358.132,"duration":0.69},{"text":"Yes, it does.","start":3358.132,"stop":3359.716,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) with license.","start":3359.716,"stop":3361.612,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":3361.612,"stop":3362.771,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Where did you quote that out?","start":3362.771,"stop":3366.365,"duration":3.59},{"text":"Is it at the bottom of page 73?","start":3366.365,"stop":3368.917,"duration":2.55}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3368.917,"stop":3371.701,"duration":2.78},{"text":"That is in the first paragraph of 28-31.1.","start":3371.701,"stop":3377.267,"duration":5.57},{"text":"“No license for any terminal vehicle shall be issued except in the annual renewal of such license or upon transfer to permit replacement of a vehicle for that license.”","start":3377.267,"stop":3390.019,"duration":12.75},{"text":"Now, that is the grandfather clause of Section 28-31.1 because the record shows that at the time of the enactment of this ordinance, Parmelee was the only holder of terminal vehicle licenses.","start":3390.019,"stop":3408.003,"duration":17.98},{"text":"This phraseology, “no license for any terminal shall be issued except in the annual renewal of such license.”","start":3408.003,"stop":3413.886,"duration":5.88},{"text":"Now --","start":3413.886,"stop":3414.115,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there a 10-year limitation on that?","start":3414.115,"stop":3416.596,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3416.596,"stop":3417.333,"duration":0.74},{"text":"The 10-year ordinance was another one.","start":3417.333,"stop":3419.559,"duration":2.23},{"text":"It was laid aside.","start":3419.559,"stop":3420.181,"duration":0.62},{"text":"I mean, the 10-year proposal was one that was laid aside.","start":3420.181,"stop":3422.528,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"It never went through.","start":3422.528,"stop":3423.433,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"It never went through.","start":3423.433,"stop":3424.444,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"This went on a space that could have operated (Inaudible) --","start":3424.444,"stop":3429.451,"duration":5.01}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"It could, yes, by annual renewal.","start":3429.451,"stop":3433.384,"duration":3.93},{"text":"That -- that --","start":3433.384,"stop":3434.179,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3434.179,"stop":3435.893,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":3435.893,"stop":3437.895,"duration":2},{"text":"Or -- and it also provides that not only by annual renewal but by transfer to permit replacement of a vehicle for that license because the license applies to a vehicle but not the operator.","start":3437.895,"stop":3449.258,"duration":11.36},{"text":"Oh, well, I misquote, it applies to both -- it applies to an individual vehicle and the operator, but when the vehicle has to be replaced, you have to relicense it.","start":3449.258,"stop":3458.728,"duration":9.47}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3458.728,"stop":3465.078,"duration":6.35}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"The Court of Appeals held substantially -- well, they held that Section 28-31.1 could not be enforced against Transfer.","start":3465.078,"stop":3478.474,"duration":13.4},{"text":"Now, they didn't invalidate that provision as far as Parmelee was concerned.","start":3478.474,"stop":3484.224,"duration":5.75},{"text":"They merely held that 28-31.1 could not be enforced against Transfer.","start":3484.224,"stop":3488.722,"duration":4.5},{"text":"That's all they held.","start":3488.722,"stop":3490.003,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3490.003,"stop":3497.071,"duration":7.07}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, no, sir.","start":3497.071,"stop":3498.047,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3498.047,"stop":3501.856,"duration":3.81}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"That is under the Chapter 28 of the -- beginning on page 171 of the record.","start":3501.856,"stop":3514.703,"duration":12.85}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"I think they're summarized in page 5 of your brief.","start":3514.703,"stop":3517.591,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that is correct.","start":3517.591,"stop":3521.063,"duration":3.47},{"text":"On page 5 of my -- our brief, we summarized this as far as it applies to terminal vehicles, the provisions of Chapter 28 that begins on page 171 of the transcript.","start":3521.063,"stop":3541.187,"duration":20.12},{"text":"I'm -- I'm going to get to that.","start":3541.187,"stop":3543.341,"duration":2.15},{"text":"In fact, I'm now about to embark upon a chronological recital of the developments in respect to the regulation of the transfer operation by the City of Chicago.","start":3543.341,"stop":3557.218,"duration":13.88}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Mathews.","start":3557.218,"stop":3557.944,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3557.944,"stop":3558.435,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I hope not to interrupt the course of your -- the sequence of your argument by asking whether you understood that I understood Mr. Grossman on behalf of the City, state to this Court that 28-31.1, the public convenience and necessity provision, does not apply, is not in conflict.","start":3558.435,"stop":3580.735,"duration":22.3},{"text":"He didn't say specifically 202 (c) (2) but that is the effect of what he said, namely, that since that is covered, that that is an interstate commerce operation, it does not require as typically convenience, is it?","start":3580.735,"stop":3595.238,"duration":14.5},{"text":"If that was so, then the conflict with 202 (c) disappears, doesn't it?","start":3595.238,"stop":3600.774,"duration":5.54}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":3600.774,"stop":3602.142,"duration":1.37},{"text":"However, Your Honor, that argument first appears -- that statement, first appears in Mr. Grossman's oral argument in this Court.","start":3602.142,"stop":3617.989,"duration":15.85},{"text":"It is contrary to Mr. Grossman's personal position in the courts below.","start":3617.989,"stop":3622.772,"duration":4.78},{"text":"It is contrary to the official position of the City of Chicago in the courts below.","start":3622.772,"stop":3626.084,"duration":3.31}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What about the position of the lower courts?","start":3626.084,"stop":3629.612,"duration":3.53},{"text":"Can they rule that 28-31.1 does apply?","start":3629.612,"stop":3635.37,"duration":5.76},{"text":"And if they have so ruled, is there a ruling to govern in view of the fact that we don't know what the ruling of the Illinois courts would be?","start":3635.37,"stop":3644.732,"duration":9.36}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I think there -- I think the answer is that the -- the Court of the -- United States District Court and Court of Appeals of the Seventh Circuit, both held that the 28-31.1 is applicable to this Transfer operation and they did so at the particular behest of the City of Chicago who urged that this applies.","start":3644.732,"stop":3666.278,"duration":21.55},{"text":"Now, as far as the question of construction by the state courts, I want to pay attention to that a little bit later on.","start":3666.278,"stop":3674.95,"duration":8.67}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":3674.95,"stop":3676.637,"duration":1.69},{"text":"I'm probably contented.","start":3676.637,"stop":3678.541,"duration":1.9},{"text":"If he's right, then this argument disappears.","start":3678.541,"stop":3681.374,"duration":2.83},{"text":"If he's right as a matter of law, then this argument of conflict with 202 (c) (2) disappears.","start":3681.374,"stop":3687.388,"duration":6.01}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3687.388,"stop":3687.788,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't that true?","start":3687.788,"stop":3689.447,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I don't like -- I don't like to engage in personalities but I'm going to add one more qualification to that if he's right as a matter of law.","start":3689.447,"stop":3697.131,"duration":7.68}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that's it.","start":3697.131,"stop":3697.822,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"And if he can bind the City Council of the City of Chicago which I doubt that the argument disappears.","start":3697.822,"stop":3706.211,"duration":8.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"There's one more thing that he said.","start":3706.211,"stop":3708.052,"duration":1.84},{"text":"Whether he's right or wrong, if the Supreme Court of Illinois has not yet spoken and if the Supreme Court of Illinois might tomorrow so speak, then we've got the kind of a problem that we've -- to which we've adverted several times in over the years?","start":3708.052,"stop":3722.313,"duration":14.26}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3722.313,"stop":3723.301,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But you took your time indeed for that.","start":3723.301,"stop":3724.631,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- you would have if certain things were true, but you don't have, Your Honor.","start":3724.631,"stop":3727.703,"duration":3.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right, I'll leave you --","start":3727.703,"stop":3728.548,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll get to that.","start":3728.548,"stop":3729.175,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":3729.175,"stop":3730.332,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":3730.332,"stop":3730.693,"duration":0.36},{"text":"Now we -- we, for many years, the City of Chicago has regulated the interstation transfer service that is prior to October 1 of 1955.","start":3730.693,"stop":3751.432,"duration":20.74},{"text":"The interstation transfer service had been performed by Parmelee Transportation Company as agent of the railroads.","start":3751.432,"stop":3760.077,"duration":8.65},{"text":"And the City of Chicago, by Chapter 28 of the Chicago Municipal Code, had regulated the operation and those provisions are summarized on page five of our brief and they include licensing for purpose of regulation, a $25 license fee for defrayal of the cost of regulation, and various of the common safety regulations ordinarily embraced in the general term police power.","start":3760.077,"stop":3793.232,"duration":33.15},{"text":"Now, I believe the sequence of -- chronological sequence of events, the calendar sequence of events is extremely important here not only on the merits of the controversy but on the point that it has been talked about by Mr. Justice Frankfurter, namely, on the construction and the application of the ordinance.","start":3793.232,"stop":3811.985,"duration":18.75},{"text":"On June 13, 1955, the railroads publicly announced that as of October 1, 1955 they were discontinuing their arrangements with Parmelee and that they had made a contract with a new corporation, Railroad Transfer Service, Incorporated, the party here, and that beginning with October 1, 1955, Railroad Transfer Service, Incorporated would take over the transfer operation of passengers between stations in Chicago that had been conducted by Parmelee.","start":3811.985,"stop":3847.838,"duration":35.85}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Was that -- was that like the Union station here I believe?","start":3847.838,"stop":3850.591,"duration":2.75},{"text":"Was that a corporation in which all the railroads had (Voice Overlap) --","start":3850.591,"stop":3854.669,"duration":4.08}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3854.669,"stop":3855.609,"duration":0.94},{"text":"I'd like to clear that out.","start":3855.609,"stop":3858.494,"duration":2.89},{"text":"No railroad --","start":3858.494,"stop":3858.786,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I know that it's relevant, it wouldn't be?","start":3858.786,"stop":3860.479,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but I want to say it.","start":3860.479,"stop":3861.648,"duration":1.17},{"text":"No railroad owns or any railroad man owns a nickel's worth of interest in Railroad Transfer Service Incorporated.","start":3861.648,"stop":3868.528,"duration":6.88},{"text":"It's -- it's strictly outside.","start":3868.528,"stop":3874.247,"duration":5.72},{"text":"The -- but as I said, on June 13, the railroads made that announcement.","start":3874.247,"stop":3880.316,"duration":6.07},{"text":"Parmelee immediately communicated that information to the Chairman of the Public Transportation Committee of the Chicago City Council who was, of course, an older body.","start":3880.316,"stop":3895.296,"duration":14.98},{"text":"On June 16, three days later, the Chairman of the Committee introduced in the Chicago City Council an ordinance that would have given Parmelee a 10-year exclusive franchise to transport -- to transfer railway passengers of any sort between the railway stations in Chicago.","start":3895.296,"stop":3917.999,"duration":22.7},{"text":"That ordinance was laid aside.","start":3917.999,"stop":3921.014,"duration":3.02},{"text":"It never came before the City Council.","start":3921.014,"stop":3923.931,"duration":2.92},{"text":"The ordinance is commented upon by the Court of Appeals and it appears in the record.","start":3923.931,"stop":3930.511,"duration":6.58},{"text":"But it's -- the only -- its only importance here is just the face of the history.","start":3930.511,"stop":3939.237,"duration":8.73},{"text":"However, on July 26th, 1955, the City of Chicago passed the ordinance that appears on pages 44 and 45 of the record and which is also set out on pages 7 and 8 of our brief.","start":3939.237,"stop":3960.231,"duration":20.99},{"text":"Now, the council also amended two other -- another provision of the ordinance.","start":3960.231,"stop":3972.513,"duration":12.28},{"text":"Prior to this amendment, the ordinance provided that no one should have a license, a terminal vehicle license, that is to transport passengers between Chicago passenger stations unless he had a contract with one or more railroads.","start":3972.513,"stop":3990.605,"duration":18.09},{"text":"This ordinance of July 26th, 1955 repealed that provision and left it wide open.","start":3990.605,"stop":4000.55,"duration":9.95},{"text":"I mean, it no longer made a necessity of having a contract with the railroads as a -- to obtain a terminal vehicle license, but it did then go ahead in Section 28-31.1 and did two things.","start":4000.55,"stop":4016.61,"duration":16.06},{"text":"It, in effect, said that gave -- gave permanent, perpetual automatic grandfather rights to all license that's outstanding, and the record is clear that they were held by Parmelee.","start":4016.61,"stop":4030.434,"duration":13.82},{"text":"Then it provided that no one else, and that might just as well have said that Railroad Transfer Service Incorporated shall not obtain a terminal vehicle license until they have applied to the public vehicle license commissioner for terminal vehicle licenses, and the public vehicle license commissioner has found that public convenience and necessity require the issue of the licenses and the -- the various categories of considerations that the public vehicle license commissioner can take into consideration including paragraph (4), “Any other facts which the commissioner may deem relevant.”","start":4030.434,"stop":4077.048,"duration":46.61},{"text":"Now, I want to read just a few lines to refer to that ordinance power of the City Council.","start":4077.048,"stop":4083.86,"duration":6.81},{"text":"The ordinance goes further said, “If the Commissioner shall report --,” and I'm reading from page eight of my brief, “If the Commissioner shall report that public convenience and necessity require additional terminal vehicle service, the council by ordinance may fix the maximum number of terminal vehicle licenses to be issued not to exceed the number recommended by the Commissioner.”","start":4083.86,"stop":4107.529,"duration":23.67},{"text":"Now, the Court of Appeals, as I said earlier, held that that particular provision obstructed the interstate transfer of passengers by motor vehicle and was invalid.","start":4107.529,"stop":4125.022,"duration":17.49},{"text":"The Court of Appeals also said that all of the rest of the ordinance was valid and applicable and there's no dispute about that.","start":4125.022,"stop":4132.52,"duration":7.5},{"text":"Now, I just want to call this to your attention.","start":4132.52,"stop":4136.198,"duration":3.68},{"text":"That if the judgment of the Court of Appeals is affirmed, we certainly think it should be, the situation in respect to the transfer of passengers in Chicago and the regulation by the City of Chicago will be precisely the same as the -- will be precisely the same regulation to which Parmelee was subject for many years.","start":4136.198,"stop":4166.321,"duration":30.12},{"text":"There'd be no change in it at all.","start":4166.321,"stop":4167.859,"duration":1.54},{"text":"The only difference will be that Transfer instead of Parmelee will be the railroads' transfer agent.","start":4167.859,"stop":4175.477,"duration":7.62},{"text":"In other words, to paraphrase the famous phrase, we think that what was good enough for Parmelee over the years is good enough for Transfer.","start":4175.477,"stop":4186.238,"duration":10.76},{"text":"And that is the effect of the judgment of the Court of Appeals.","start":4186.238,"stop":4189.813,"duration":3.57}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What are the areas of regulation that would be -- you would be subject to?","start":4189.813,"stop":4195.98,"duration":6.17}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"A license for identification.","start":4195.98,"stop":4198.732,"duration":2.75},{"text":"A $25 license fee for, I presume it's not a tax.","start":4198.732,"stop":4202.228,"duration":3.5},{"text":"I presumed it's a police-power fee for defrayment of the cost of regulation, various requirements to have a clean and sanitary and safe vehicle, filing of insurance policies with the City, and I think you can say in general summary, just the various ordinary police power regulations of traffic in a large city.","start":4202.228,"stop":4234.409,"duration":32.18},{"text":"Now, I want to call -- in that connection, I'd like to call your attention to this.","start":4234.409,"stop":4239.838,"duration":5.43},{"text":"This 1955 amendment that the Court of Appeals held invalid was not like some motor vehicle regulatory ordinances that are -- or laws that this Court has held valid.","start":4239.838,"stop":4257.358,"duration":17.52},{"text":"This was not aimed at a type of traffic deemed undesirable or as to which particular regulation was required because of this fact that Parmelee was given perpetual grandfather rights to operate.","start":4257.358,"stop":4274.854,"duration":17.5},{"text":"In other words, the City Council of the City of Chicago was not striking at the industry or at a type of vehicle operation.","start":4274.854,"stop":4283.329,"duration":8.47},{"text":"For instance, like it wasn't saying that nobody can operate if his truck weighs over so much or that a particular type -- specialized-type of motor vehicle traffic can be taxed higher than other types.","start":4283.329,"stop":4296.154,"duration":12.83},{"text":"They were merely saying -- they were merely saying the City Council of the City of Chicago is going to arrogate to itself to determine who shall engage in interstate commerce.","start":4296.154,"stop":4308.398,"duration":12.24},{"text":"And the Supreme Court of the -- this Court has held beginning back with Gibbons against Ogden and in numerous cases since, that the States have no right to say, who on a selected basis between two types of candidates or operators, the States have no power to say who to select, who shall engage in interstate commerce.","start":4308.398,"stop":4332.813,"duration":24.41},{"text":"That as a matter of fact, I think may not be entirely relevant right at this point of the argument but I think that this case presents a very striking parallel to Gibbons against Ogden because the State of New York didn't object to steamboats at all on the rivers.","start":4332.813,"stop":4353.364,"duration":20.55},{"text":"All it said was that any steamboat that operates on the river must have a license from the State of New York and we won't let any other steamboats operate on the river.","start":4353.364,"stop":4365.435,"duration":12.07},{"text":"Gibbons had a federal posting license which certainly if you will examine the Old Posting License Act.","start":4365.435,"stop":4373.725,"duration":8.29},{"text":"It actually gave less powers and imposed less duties than Section 202 (c) (2) of the Interstate Commerce Act.","start":4373.725,"stop":4380.993,"duration":7.27},{"text":"But in Gibbons against Ogden, this Court held that the Federal Posting License Act superseded the power of the State of New York to grant an exclusive license to Fulton and Livingston for steamboat traffic.","start":4380.993,"stop":4392.635,"duration":11.64},{"text":"And if Your Honors please, the City of Chicago, some 130 or more years later is trying here to do precisely what this Court said the State of New York could not do in Gibbons against Ogden.","start":4392.635,"stop":4405.064,"duration":12.43},{"text":"As a matter of interest --","start":4405.064,"stop":4406.143,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Does Parmelee -- does Parmelee have a certificate on the Interstate Commerce Commission?","start":4406.143,"stop":4409.837,"duration":3.69}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir, and neither does Transfer.","start":4409.837,"stop":4413.631,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well has Parmelee had one heretofore?","start":4413.631,"stop":4415.707,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":4415.707,"stop":4417.269,"duration":1.56},{"text":"Under -- we do not need in order to -- you see, under Section 202 (c) (2), it is the railroads who are performing the service.","start":4417.269,"stop":4432.177,"duration":14.91},{"text":"And under Section 202 (c) (2), the -- the railroads have the authority under the Interstate Commerce Act to operate and it is a railroad operation, so that the agent who is operating for them does not need any authority.","start":4432.177,"stop":4451.169,"duration":18.99},{"text":"The agent operates under the authority of the railroads.","start":4451.169,"stop":4455.556,"duration":4.39},{"text":"That -- that is very clear under the decisions.","start":4455.556,"stop":4459.688,"duration":4.13},{"text":"The -- illustrating that is the -- are the decisions of this Court holding that in -- in grandfather rights cases where an agent has been operating during the grandfather period for a motor carrier and performing all of the physical services, the motor carrier itself gets a grandfather rights and not the agent.","start":4459.688,"stop":4494.084,"duration":34.4},{"text":"In other words, the -- under Section 202 (c) (2), the transfer is in fact simply its identity is merged into the identity of the railroads for purpose of regulation.","start":4494.084,"stop":4508.483,"duration":14.4},{"text":"So neither it nor Parmelee, in performing this service for the railroads, needs a certificate.","start":4508.483,"stop":4515.804,"duration":7.32},{"text":"Now --","start":4515.804,"stop":4516.054,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Did the railroads (Voice Overlap) excuse me.","start":4516.054,"stop":4518.094,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Go on.","start":4518.094,"stop":4518.215,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Did the railroads have a certificate?","start":4518.215,"stop":4520.55,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Not to perform the motor carrier operation.","start":4520.55,"stop":4522.52,"duration":1.97},{"text":"Of course, the railroads have permanent grandfather rights under the Part 1 one of the Interstate Commerce Act to operate passenger trains and ships into Chicago.","start":4522.52,"stop":4534.771,"duration":12.25},{"text":"And by Section 202 (c) (2) of the Interstate Commerce Act, the railroads are given perpetual franchises to operate motor vehicles in transfer, collection, or delivery service within terminal areas.","start":4534.771,"stop":4550.945,"duration":16.17},{"text":"That's where the -- in other words, if it were not for Section 202 (c) (2), any person performing this service or the railroads if they were performing it themselves, would have to have a certificate under part two of the Interstate Commerce Act; the certificate of public convenience and necessity.","start":4550.945,"stop":4569.032,"duration":18.09},{"text":"But Section 202 (c) gives the railroads in effect, permanent certificates of public convenience and necessity.","start":4569.032,"stop":4581.279,"duration":12.25},{"text":"Grant a permanent grandfather rights I suppose they could be styled to conduct this terminal operation.","start":4581.279,"stop":4587.575,"duration":6.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I wanted to ask whether prior to June 30, 1955, Parmelee was the exclusive terminal vehicle service as between the railroad terminal in Chicago.","start":4587.575,"stop":4599.912,"duration":12.34}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":4599.912,"stop":4600.932,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And was that because of 202 (c) (2) or that is to allow the railroads to define by the tariff who shall do the shuttling?","start":4600.932,"stop":4610.415,"duration":9.48},{"text":"Is that right?","start":4610.415,"stop":4612.79,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it goes -- does more than that.","start":4612.79,"stop":4614.546,"duration":1.76},{"text":"It -- it relieves them of the necessity of applying to the commission for a certificate.","start":4614.546,"stop":4619.246,"duration":4.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that, but the exclusiveness doesn't derive from that.","start":4619.246,"stop":4624.574,"duration":5.33},{"text":"The exclusiveness --","start":4624.574,"stop":4626.319,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"It derives from the contract.","start":4626.319,"stop":4627.731,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"From the contract.","start":4627.731,"stop":4628.575,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4628.575,"stop":4629.444,"duration":0.87},{"text":"Oh, yes.","start":4629.444,"stop":4630.807,"duration":1.36},{"text":"Well, did this answer your question?","start":4630.807,"stop":4633.062,"duration":2.26},{"text":"The railroads, if they wanted to --","start":4633.062,"stop":4633.903,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The exclusiveness -- the exclusiveness so far as the railroads are concerned, derives from the contract, but does that exclude anybody else within Chicago?","start":4633.903,"stop":4644.06,"duration":10.16},{"text":"And if it did, if that exclusiveness doesn't -- did the City of Chicago have anything to do with that?","start":4644.06,"stop":4651.602,"duration":7.54},{"text":"Did the City of Chicago say, “We won't authorize other people to do that carriage between the termini?","start":4651.602,"stop":4659.024,"duration":7.42},{"text":"Take for instance, who don't take -- who take interstate carriers who do not have a through ticket.","start":4659.024,"stop":4665.147,"duration":6.12},{"text":"I'm probably assuming an unreal situation, but take a person who comes in from out of Chicago, out of Illinois into Chicago and then transfers to another railroad, buys another ticket and get to New York.","start":4665.147,"stop":4677.159,"duration":12.01},{"text":"And of course, that's very unreal.","start":4677.159,"stop":4679.053,"duration":1.89},{"text":"Could he -- could he or she pick up some taxi without any contract relation?","start":4679.053,"stop":4685.832,"duration":6.78}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes.","start":4685.832,"stop":4686.63,"duration":0.8},{"text":"Yes.","start":4686.63,"stop":4687.6,"duration":0.97},{"text":"And --","start":4687.6,"stop":4688.244,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You can do it if you have it.","start":4688.244,"stop":4690.128,"duration":1.88},{"text":"If you have through tickets, you can do just the same, could you?","start":4690.128,"stop":4693.006,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes, but that is if you wanted to -- wanted to lose the value of (Voice Overlap) --","start":4693.006,"stop":4696.493,"duration":3.49}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4696.493,"stop":4697.576,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But -- but the service that the vehicles that are allowed to coast around the different termini maybe regulated by Chicago even though it involved interstate transfers.","start":4697.576,"stop":4708.644,"duration":11.07},{"text":"Is that right or not?","start":4708.644,"stop":4709.601,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes.","start":4709.601,"stop":4711.096,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now what I'm asking is --","start":4711.096,"stop":4713.251,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"If I understand your question, right -- I'm sorry, go ahead.","start":4713.251,"stop":4716.658,"duration":3.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I want to put the question clearly if I can.","start":4716.658,"stop":4718.837,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I believe I do.","start":4718.837,"stop":4719.72,"duration":0.88},{"text":"Yes.","start":4719.72,"stop":4719.871,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4719.871,"stop":4720.61,"duration":0.74},{"text":"Now by what -- how did it come that Parmelee was that exclusive service for that transfer from one terminus to another?","start":4720.61,"stop":4728.718,"duration":8.11}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"The railroads entered into an arrangement with Parmelee.","start":4728.718,"stop":4730.868,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And Chicago acquiesced, though it need not have acquiesced, is that it?","start":4730.868,"stop":4735.225,"duration":4.36}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Chicago did acquiesce in this -- to this extent that --","start":4735.225,"stop":4739.051,"duration":3.83}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did it have any say in the matter?","start":4739.051,"stop":4740.446,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, yes.","start":4740.446,"stop":4741.171,"duration":0.73},{"text":"They did this because, as I said prior to July 26, 1955, the ordinance provided that no one could have a license to transfer passengers unless he had a contract with the railroad.","start":4741.171,"stop":4753.05,"duration":11.88}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And was that within the power of Chicago?","start":4753.05,"stop":4755.798,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know.","start":4755.798,"stop":4757.103,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, do you think it was?","start":4757.103,"stop":4761.174,"duration":4.07}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I've never even thought of that and it's a (Voice Overlap)","start":4761.174,"stop":4766.978,"duration":5.8}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did they become relevant to this question, Mr. Mathews.","start":4766.978,"stop":4771.936,"duration":4.96}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, maybe I can approach it from this angle.","start":4771.936,"stop":4775.964,"duration":4.03},{"text":"Under Section 202 (c) (2), I think the railroads have a right to select their agent.","start":4775.964,"stop":4782.514,"duration":6.55}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4782.514,"stop":4785.119,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, I can see -- as long as the railroads have that right under the Interstate Commerce Act, I can see no reason why Chicago can't say, “Well, alright.","start":4785.119,"stop":4800.265,"duration":15.15},{"text":"We'll --,” or conversely, the City of Chicago can say, “We'll give a terminal vehicle license to anyone who has a contract with the railroads.”","start":4800.265,"stop":4810.631,"duration":10.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Or -- or who hasn't?","start":4810.631,"stop":4812.035,"duration":1.4},{"text":"Or who hasn't?","start":4812.035,"stop":4812.653,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Or -- yes, they could do that.","start":4812.653,"stop":4816.567,"duration":3.91},{"text":"Oh -- oh I'm -- the City of Chicago can let anybody operate.","start":4816.567,"stop":4822.044,"duration":5.48},{"text":"But the City of Chicago can't say to the railroads, “You've got to divide your business among John Doe and Richard Row and Parmelee and Transfer.”","start":4822.044,"stop":4830.819,"duration":8.78},{"text":"That's what I mean.","start":4830.819,"stop":4831.71,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But can't it say for traffic consideration, if that is conceivable, that we want to give a choice to the mass or to the 3900 people who pour into Chicago everyday because the actual service of traffic -- of shuttling, which the railroads are providing by their own arrangements, don't seem to be adequate, block the traffic, etcetera, etcetera.","start":4831.71,"stop":4851.805,"duration":20.1}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I don't think they can under the Interstate Commerce Act.","start":4851.805,"stop":4853.928,"duration":2.12},{"text":"No.","start":4853.928,"stop":4855.679,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Mathews, may I ask you this question.","start":4855.679,"stop":4859.334,"duration":3.65},{"text":"Is it conceded by both sides that under this opinion of the court below, Parmelee can continue to transfer passengers from one station to another, only, it does it on its own independently and not by contract with the -- with the railroads?","start":4859.334,"stop":4884,"duration":24.67}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I certainly concede that and if I understand Mr. Grossman correctly, I think he does.","start":4884,"stop":4888.426,"duration":4.43}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4888.426,"stop":4889,"duration":0.57},{"text":"Well Mr. -- Mr. Grossman --","start":4889,"stop":4890.732,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4890.732,"stop":4891.218,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and I just had an agreement.","start":4891.218,"stop":4892.984,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4892.984,"stop":4893.913,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4893.913,"stop":4894.239,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Just as an independent operation.","start":4894.239,"stop":4896.06,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"So this does not put Parmelee out of business --","start":4896.06,"stop":4897.939,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, no.","start":4897.939,"stop":4898.843,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"If -- if they can still operate --","start":4898.843,"stop":4900.931,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":4900.931,"stop":4901.297,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- they can still operate.","start":4901.297,"stop":4902.093,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it's not in the record.","start":4902.093,"stop":4903.082,"duration":0.99},{"text":"It's not in the record and I don't know that I've seen them lately.","start":4903.082,"stop":4907.027,"duration":3.94},{"text":"But for a long time after Transfer started to operate, the Parmelee vehicles were parked right outside the stations.","start":4907.027,"stop":4917.242,"duration":10.22},{"text":"And I suppose they got passengers, although I never actually saw anybody get into their vehicles, I never once.","start":4917.242,"stop":4923.517,"duration":6.27}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Do the taxis in Chicago at this terminal -- are they local -- Yellow or some other taxi company?","start":4923.517,"stop":4929.608,"duration":6.09}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes.","start":4929.608,"stop":4930.536,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But they can't come in to this terminus?","start":4930.536,"stop":4933.074,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes, they do.","start":4933.074,"stop":4933.913,"duration":0.84},{"text":"They come right into the terminus.","start":4933.913,"stop":4935.893,"duration":1.98},{"text":"You can -- in any station in Chicago, you can get out of your train and ride under the train ship.","start":4935.893,"stop":4942.231,"duration":6.34},{"text":"There will be taxi cab service of yellow, brown, black, and white.","start":4942.231,"stop":4946.699,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And what is it that you wanted to stop Parmelee from doing?","start":4946.699,"stop":4949.573,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"We don't want to stop Parmelee from doing anything.","start":4949.573,"stop":4952.149,"duration":2.58},{"text":"All we want is the right to operate our transfer vehicles as we're authorized to do under the Interstate Commerce Act, and the City of Chicago says you can't do that.","start":4952.149,"stop":4962.846,"duration":10.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Without getting a license.","start":4962.846,"stop":4964.157,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Without having the -- no without having the City of Chicago pass an ordinance saying that we can do it.","start":4964.157,"stop":4972.944,"duration":8.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That is on the assumption.","start":4972.944,"stop":4974.334,"duration":1.39},{"text":"That is on the assumption that Mr. Grossman's position here for the necessity of finding out whether his position is right or wrong has to be determined by Illinois Courts subject to that to which you --","start":4974.334,"stop":4986.226,"duration":11.89}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":4986.226,"stop":4987.04,"duration":0.81},{"text":"No, I'd like to -- I'd like to go to that point now.","start":4987.04,"stop":4988.879,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":4988.879,"stop":4989.29,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't have much time remaining but I would like to go to that point.","start":4989.29,"stop":4996.35,"duration":7.06}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm thinking of a case like expected that we had some years ago.","start":4996.35,"stop":4998.427,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that's it exactly.","start":4998.427,"stop":4999.703,"duration":1.28},{"text":"Well --","start":4999.703,"stop":5000.162,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":5000.162,"stop":5000.445,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"-- if Your Honor please, I'm thinking of a case like Toomer against Witsell in which this Court held that where these -- the state law is clear -- where the state statute or an ordinance is perfectly clear on the States and it's perfectly clear and everybody has agreed what it does and what it's intended to do that it's just simply, either gestured or remitted to the state courts, that's what this Court decided in Toomer against Witsell.","start":5000.445,"stop":5025.593,"duration":25.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but we are troubled if we have the law preserve the City of Chicago, a City with a great deal of assurance.","start":5025.593,"stop":5031.525,"duration":5.93}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, well now, let me go to that.","start":5031.525,"stop":5033.753,"duration":2.23},{"text":"Let me go to that point right now.","start":5033.753,"stop":5050.298,"duration":16.55},{"text":"This -- this argument that was made by Mr. Grossman in the last 15 or 20 minutes he made, is something new in the case and if I may give my own personal view of it, I think it's a kind of a wheel of the west to get us all back into the morass in which the railroads and Transfer found themselves in the fall of 1955, and I will now proceed to tell you why.","start":5050.298,"stop":5081.67,"duration":31.37},{"text":"The railroads and Transfer in their complaint in the District Court made this allegation and this is a form of allegation I'll admit but it happened to be true.","start":5081.67,"stop":5094.927,"duration":13.26},{"text":"The railroad said this --","start":5094.927,"stop":5096.169,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What page is that in your brief?","start":5096.169,"stop":5097.078,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"That's on pages 6 and 7 of the record, paragraph (4) of page 6 and 7 of the record.","start":5097.078,"stop":5107.391,"duration":10.31},{"text":"“The terminal lines and Transfer have specifically and repeatedly advised the defendant in the City of Chicago through the defendant's Daley, the mayor, Melaniphy and Flynn, its duly elected or appointed officials that the provisions of said ordinance did not apply to the operations of Transfer pursuant to the agency contract.","start":5107.391,"stop":5126.132,"duration":18.74},{"text":"And further, that a said ordinance did apply to such operations, said ordinance was void as an attempt to regulate interstate commerce and contravention of the Commerce Clause despite said advice.”","start":5126.132,"stop":5137.589,"duration":11.46},{"text":"Now, these are allegations of fact, particularly this one.","start":5137.589,"stop":5142.428,"duration":4.84},{"text":"Despite said advice, the defendant in the City of Chicago, acting through the defendant's Daley, Melaniphy, O'Connor, and Flynn, its duly authorized officials, has asserted and continues to assert that the ordinance is valid and enforceable against Transfer.","start":5142.428,"stop":5157.124,"duration":14.7},{"text":"And that the Defendant, the City of Chicago, acting through its officers, agents, servants, and employees, would attempt to enforce said ordinance against Transfer as a violator thereof by arresting Transfer's drivers operating its passenger motor vehicles and so forth.”","start":5157.124,"stop":5172.956,"duration":15.83},{"text":"Well, one more important line, “Used in the performance of Transfer's operations under the agency contract.”","start":5172.956,"stop":5179.787,"duration":6.83},{"text":"Now, those are allegations of fact and they were all admitted by the motion of the defendants for summary judgment.","start":5179.787,"stop":5192.087,"duration":12.3},{"text":"That's not only true, of course, as a matter of law but the defendant stated in their motion for summary judgment in pages 71, 72 of the record.","start":5192.087,"stop":5199.079,"duration":6.99}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you.","start":5199.079,"stop":5199.7,"duration":0.62},{"text":"That said violating the ordinance if the terminal vehicle licenses are the ones which you say requires you to get a certificate of convenience and necessity, or is it a different kind?","start":5199.7,"stop":5215.403,"duration":15.7}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"It is.","start":5215.403,"stop":5215.932,"duration":0.53},{"text":"It is the one that under the amendment of 1955 requires us to get a certificate of convenience and necessity under 28-31.1.","start":5215.932,"stop":5227.303,"duration":11.37},{"text":"But it is the -- before 28-31.1 was enacted in July of 1955, the terminal vehicle license did not require proof of public convenience and necessity, but the terminal vehicle license that he's talked about here is the one that requires proof of public convenience and necessity under 28-31.1.","start":5227.303,"stop":5247.53,"duration":20.23}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"How do we know that if the law wasn't in effect at that time this complaint was made?","start":5247.53,"stop":5252.835,"duration":5.31}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, the law was in effect.","start":5252.835,"stop":5254.024,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The law was in effect.","start":5254.024,"stop":5255.495,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"This complaint was filed October 24, 1955.","start":5255.495,"stop":5259.508,"duration":4.01}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"After the ordinance --","start":5259.508,"stop":5260.162,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"After the ordinance went into effect.","start":5260.162,"stop":5261.45,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And it's clear I presume from both argues then that this charges that they were threatening you if you did not get a certificate of convenience and necessity under 31?","start":5261.45,"stop":5272.298,"duration":10.85}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes, and in other -- other --","start":5272.298,"stop":5274.282,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"He shakes his head off.","start":5274.282,"stop":5276.09,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, --","start":5276.09,"stop":5277.522,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"[Laughs]","start":5277.522,"stop":5279.505,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"-- all I can say is this.","start":5279.505,"stop":5281.475,"duration":1.97},{"text":"That in paragraph (4), it's plain English and in -- in the City's motion for summary judgment they said this --","start":5281.475,"stop":5293.967,"duration":12.49}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What page is that?","start":5293.967,"stop":5295.34,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"71 and 72 of the record.","start":5295.34,"stop":5299.867,"duration":4.53}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":5299.867,"stop":5305.716,"duration":5.85}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- that's correct.","start":5305.716,"stop":5307.319,"duration":1.6},{"text":"That's correct, but I merely wanted to point out that they gilded to lily or frosted the cake or something by saying, “In support of said motion, defendant state that there is no genuine issue as to any material fact contained in the complaint.”","start":5307.319,"stop":5320.106,"duration":12.79},{"text":"Now, in other words, they admitted that they would arrest their drivers under the agency contract.","start":5320.106,"stop":5326.521,"duration":6.41},{"text":"Now, they're talking about the operation under this contract.","start":5326.521,"stop":5329.673,"duration":3.15},{"text":"They're talking about that specifically.","start":5329.673,"stop":5331.091,"duration":1.42},{"text":"Well, let's go on a little way.","start":5331.091,"stop":5334.42,"duration":3.33},{"text":"The District Court filed a memorandum opinion in which the District Court held the ordinance valid and enforceable and applicable against this operation.","start":5334.42,"stop":5348.245,"duration":13.82},{"text":"That was the whole business including this public convenience and necessity requirement.","start":5348.245,"stop":5353.231,"duration":4.99},{"text":"And as is customary, the District Court asked counsel to supply proposed findings of fact and conclusions of law.","start":5353.231,"stop":5362.283,"duration":9.05},{"text":"And in paragraph (2) of the proposed conclusion of law submitted by the City, by Mr. Grossman in-person, and that is on page 122 of the record, this was the conclusion of law submitted.","start":5362.283,"stop":5379.151,"duration":16.87},{"text":"“Transfer operates its motor vehicles on public ways for the transportation of passengers for hire from place to place within the corporate limits of the City as provided in Section 28-2 of the ordinance.","start":5379.151,"stop":5394.103,"duration":14.95},{"text":"Now, Section 28-2 of the ordinance is the fishnet or the drag net that catches everybody.","start":5394.103,"stop":5398.873,"duration":4.77},{"text":"If you're within 28-2, you're within the ordinance, and that was Mr. Grossman's own contribution to the final judgment of the District Court.","start":5398.873,"stop":5412.666,"duration":13.79},{"text":"That -- that -- and that was the City's position.","start":5412.666,"stop":5418.263,"duration":5.6},{"text":"Well, and I should add to that that in the record 155, 159, Conclusion of Law Number 5, the District Court adopted that conclusion recommended by Mr. Grossman.","start":5418.263,"stop":5437.186,"duration":18.92},{"text":"Now -- and the District Court specifically held as a conclusion of law and dismissed our complaint.","start":5437.186,"stop":5446.836,"duration":9.65},{"text":"In other words, and held that the whole ordinance including this public convenience and necessity section was enforceable against us.","start":5446.836,"stop":5456.963,"duration":10.13},{"text":"We appealed to the Court of Appeals.","start":5456.963,"stop":5459.192,"duration":2.23},{"text":"Now, what did the City do there?","start":5459.192,"stop":5465.735,"duration":6.54},{"text":"The City came in and by its -- we have filed a certified copy of the City's brief and all of the briefs in the Court of Appeals for that matter with this Court.","start":5465.735,"stop":5475.515,"duration":9.78},{"text":"And so I -- and I have set out in -- I set out on page 14 of our brief the quotation from the Court, from the City's brief in the Court of Appeals.","start":5475.515,"stop":5493.359,"duration":17.84},{"text":"Now, keep in mind that this brief in the Court of Appeals and the City's official brief signed by the corporation council and the paragraph, I won't read all of the paragraph, but on -- I call your attention to that language on page 14 of our brief that the framers of the ordinance in question intended to regulate the business carried on by Transfer wholly within the City of Chicago as hardly subject to challenge.","start":5493.359,"stop":5521.599,"duration":28.24},{"text":"Now that's what the City was seeing back in the Court of Appeals and down at the -- and then the City goes ahead in its brief and quotes several sections of the ordinance including 28-1.","start":5521.599,"stop":5536.283,"duration":14.68},{"text":"And the City lines up its discussion by saying in the last sentence, “A more accurate description of the business engaged in by Transfer would be hard to find.”","start":5536.283,"stop":5546.928,"duration":10.64},{"text":"Now, if the Court please, after the City of Chicago has obtained in the District Court and in the Court of Appeals, at its own request and upon its own solemn assurances to those two Courts, that this ordinance is applicable to the transfer operation, can counsel for the City come before this Court and make a representation to say that the City does not so contend?","start":5546.928,"stop":5588.905,"duration":41.98},{"text":"If he can, why then, we might just as well abolish all the rules of procedure and litigation.As a matter of fact, he couldn't make that contention in the Illinois courts.","start":5588.905,"stop":5599.937,"duration":11.03},{"text":"I call your attention to the City of Chicago against the University of Chicago cited on page 15 of our brief.","start":5599.937,"stop":5607.926,"duration":7.99},{"text":"In that case, the City Council of the City of Chicago had taken the position in the trial court, in the Circuit Court that a certain ordinance was valid.","start":5607.926,"stop":5622.29,"duration":14.36},{"text":"And then as suit of their convenience or suit of their -- they want to suit their convenience as in this case, they took the position before the Supreme Court of Illinois that the ordinance was invalid.","start":5622.29,"stop":5634.275,"duration":11.98},{"text":"And here is what the Supreme Court of Illinois said and I think that is what the rule of this Court should follow in this case.","start":5634.275,"stop":5643.257,"duration":8.98},{"text":"“Having alleged the validity of the ordinance in its pleading and proceeded to a hearing on that theory, the City cannot now be heard to say that the Circuit Court erred in adopting its view.”","start":5643.257,"stop":5656.772,"duration":13.52},{"text":"And to paraphrase that, Your Honors, we say that having alleged in the District Court and in the Court of Appeals of the Seventh Circuit that the ordinance is applicable including the public convenience and necessity, is applicable to the transfer operation from having one on both issues, mind you that both courts -- the courts decided those two issues in favor of the City, the City cannot now be heard to say that the Court of Appeals of the Seventh Circuit erred in adopting its view.","start":5656.772,"stop":5690.347,"duration":33.57}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But I wonder -- I'm always troubled by estoppel arguments that I gather from Judge LaBuy's memorandum that before him, you urged that you are not included within the condemnation because of the fact that this is interstate commerce.","start":5690.347,"stop":5708.829,"duration":18.48},{"text":"Is that correct?","start":5708.829,"stop":5709.727,"duration":0.9},{"text":"At least Judge LaBuy said so.","start":5709.727,"stop":5712.516,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think it would perhaps be better to go to our complaint to resolve what he said there than what LaBuy said -- Judge LaBuy said in his opinion but --","start":5712.516,"stop":5723.098,"duration":10.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The last point urged by plaintiff is that the ordinance did not intend to include the public on or exclusively devoted to interstate (Voice Overlap) issue.","start":5723.098,"stop":5731.24,"duration":8.14}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"True enough.","start":5731.24,"stop":5731.957,"duration":0.72},{"text":"We did urge that.","start":5731.957,"stop":5733.024,"duration":1.07},{"text":"But the point is that we lost.","start":5733.024,"stop":5736.287,"duration":3.26},{"text":"We lost on that issue.","start":5736.287,"stop":5736.93,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What I'm suggesting is that if you made that contention, one might infer that it isn't a wholly frivolous contention.","start":5736.93,"stop":5744.796,"duration":7.87}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think it is myself.","start":5744.796,"stop":5750.216,"duration":5.42}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose instead of making a statement here to this effect or argue that he would file a stipulation -- he had filed a stipulation representing his client, stipulating that your side is not included in the --","start":5750.216,"stop":5766.33,"duration":16.11}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, well now --","start":5766.33,"stop":5767,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That there's no controversy.","start":5767,"stop":5768.095,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's -- let's get right at that.","start":5768.095,"stop":5769.579,"duration":1.48},{"text":"Let's get right at that in the five minutes I have remaining.","start":5769.579,"stop":5775.961,"duration":6.38},{"text":"Actually, I don't believe and I haven't been able to find the case on this except some very early observations of commentators on the Constitution.","start":5775.961,"stop":5785.661,"duration":9.7},{"text":"And I can't identify them now, but I don't believe the City of Chicago can go to a Court and say, “We want you to hold that one of our ordinances does not apply to Transfer because you have before you here the legislative body.”","start":5785.661,"stop":5812.514,"duration":26.85},{"text":"The City of Chicago, if it wanted to get rid of this legislation on the theory they now suggest, could pass a two-line ordinance tomorrow saying that the public convenience and necessity provisions of this do not apply to the Transfer operation and what would happen why this whole litigation would be dismissed as moot clear back through the District Court and everything would be wiped out.","start":5812.514,"stop":5833.168,"duration":20.65},{"text":"Why doesn't the City of Chicago do that?","start":5833.168,"stop":5835.507,"duration":2.34},{"text":"They don't do it because they're just not serious.","start":5835.507,"stop":5839.115,"duration":3.61},{"text":"They just are not serious in this because every time when it has served their purpose, they have said this ordinance applied to this.","start":5839.115,"stop":5847.888,"duration":8.77},{"text":"Now, when they find a judgment holding the ordinance unconstitutional on, if I may be permitted to say so, entirely sound grounds, they take this wheel of the west gamblers to avoid their position they've taken in the courts below and get back into the Courts of Illinois.","start":5847.888,"stop":5866.192,"duration":18.3},{"text":"If they get back into the Courts of Illinois, I tell you gentlemen as a member of the bar of this Court, the City of Chicago will go to an Illinois court and they will say this ordinance applies.","start":5866.192,"stop":5878.003,"duration":11.81},{"text":"They have done that on every occasion in the past when it served their purpose and they'll do it again.","start":5878.003,"stop":5881.95,"duration":3.95},{"text":"Now, getting back then to this issue of remission to the Illinois courts.","start":5881.95,"stop":5886.82,"duration":4.87}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"So do you think you'd have any remedy if they would stipulate here to that effect and then went back to a totally different (Voice Overlap) --","start":5886.82,"stop":5892.7,"duration":5.88}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, if they were stipulated but --","start":5892.7,"stop":5895.82,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"As I gather he's saying that it doesn't apply.","start":5895.82,"stop":5900.77,"duration":4.95}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":5900.77,"stop":5901.843,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And he might say that --","start":5901.843,"stop":5902.648,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I have -- I have grave doubts about what would happen in the City Council of the City of Chicago.","start":5902.648,"stop":5914.012,"duration":11.36},{"text":"Of course, well, another thing too.","start":5914.012,"stop":5915.944,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":5915.944,"stop":5918.983,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":5918.983,"stop":5930.067,"duration":11.08}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":5930.067,"stop":5936.083,"duration":6.02},{"text":"The -- as a matter of fact, the argument on applicability, if you'll examine the complaint, was not on applicability but it was simply to the effect that since this is interstate commerce, it doesn't apply.","start":5936.083,"stop":5954.038,"duration":17.95},{"text":"Well now, it does apply in terms and is in conflict.","start":5954.038,"stop":5957.554,"duration":3.52},{"text":"Now, I want to call your attention to Toomer against Witsell and other cases cited on pages 16 and 17 of our brief, to the effect that where in this case a litigant has taken positions and -- and the statute is clear, there is no occasion for admission to state courts.","start":5957.554,"stop":5980.285,"duration":22.73},{"text":"Thank you.","start":5980.285,"stop":5983.419,"duration":3.13}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"May I have a few minutes.","start":5983.419,"stop":5984.828,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"You have one minute -- one minute or so left, Mr. Grossman, and I wish you would address yourself first to the question of whether the City of Chicago would be willing in this -- in this proceeding to stipulate that this ordinance does not apply to your cause.","start":5984.828,"stop":6006.187,"duration":21.36}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know because the City Council, of course, governed --","start":6006.187,"stop":6010.892,"duration":4.7}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't that --","start":6010.892,"stop":6011.376,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"The City Council governed the City.","start":6011.376,"stop":6013.032,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Mathews","textObjs":[{"text":"That's enough answer to -- that's enough answer to that.","start":6013.032,"stop":6015.083,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Now Your Honor, I'm surprised the counsel is saying that he is subject to license -- that his operation is subject to license when he never applied for a license and he alleged in the complaint that they are not subject to license, which he didn't read.","start":6015.083,"stop":6042.39,"duration":27.31},{"text":"It says that they threatened arrest because they were a violator of the ordinance without obtaining terminal vehicle licenses for each such passenger motor vehicle as required by Section 28-2 of said ordinance.","start":6042.39,"stop":6062.197,"duration":19.81},{"text":"Nowhere does it appear that I couldn't issue Section 28-31.1.","start":6062.197,"stop":6071.733,"duration":9.54},{"text":"All we did and when he talks about the -- the findings of fact in law, I was merely following a memorandum of Judge LaBuy, the District Court I was compelled to find the way he found, and that is that the ordinance was applicable to it.","start":6071.733,"stop":6095.358,"duration":23.63},{"text":"Nothing was said about 28-31.2 in any of my pleadings.","start":6095.358,"stop":6101.45,"duration":6.09},{"text":"I think that the -- to say the least, improper motives were attributed by the Court of Appeals and by counsel here to my remarks and to my position.","start":6101.45,"stop":6117.609,"duration":16.16},{"text":"I never took the position.","start":6117.609,"stop":6118.688,"duration":1.08},{"text":"As a matter of fact, this contest was between Parmelee and Transfer.","start":6118.688,"stop":6125.49,"duration":6.8},{"text":"Parmelee's counsel argued the case before the District Court.","start":6125.49,"stop":6130.542,"duration":5.05},{"text":"Parmelee's counsel argued the case before the United States Court of Appeals and the controversy between -- between the two.","start":6130.542,"stop":6140.066,"duration":9.52},{"text":"We were in -- the City was in the middle.","start":6140.066,"stop":6143.056,"duration":2.99},{"text":"I took the position from the beginning at 28-31.1 applied to terminal vehicles as defined and that is the new definition is that it's a local transportation facility.","start":6143.056,"stop":6161.746,"duration":18.69},{"text":"And I never -- I never deviated from that from the beginning.","start":6161.746,"stop":6167.544,"duration":5.8}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well do you take the position in this Court that this is just a fight between Parmelee and Transfer?","start":6167.544,"stop":6172.944,"duration":5.4}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly, it is.","start":6172.944,"stop":6174.594,"duration":1.65},{"text":"And -- and counsel here -- counsel here said that they are subject to license that they will proceed just as Parmelee did.","start":6174.594,"stop":6184.126,"duration":9.53},{"text":"Now, why didn't they do it?","start":6184.126,"stop":6186.13,"duration":2},{"text":"Why did they -- why did they file a suit to restrain the City from enforcing a licensing ordinance?","start":6186.13,"stop":6196.295,"duration":10.16},{"text":"That's what they did.","start":6196.295,"stop":6197.993,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":6197.993,"stop":6204.753,"duration":6.76}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph F. Grossman","textObjs":[{"text":"I saw it.","start":6204.753,"stop":6205.987,"duration":1.23},{"text":"I saw it, Your Honor.","start":6205.987,"stop":6207.953,"duration":1.97},{"text":"That was a civil rights case.","start":6207.953,"stop":6211.879,"duration":3.93},{"text":"It came up through the state courts by virtue of a conviction for violating an ordinance to that or a state statute and which -- which -- by which there were no standards fixed or the issuance of a license as I recall it.","start":6211.879,"stop":6240.608,"duration":28.73},{"text":"That is not the case here.","start":6240.608,"stop":6243.483,"duration":2.88},{"text":"I think that this ought to go to the state courts to determine whether they are subject to license although they've now admitted it.","start":6243.483,"stop":6251.158,"duration":7.68},{"text":"They've now admitted that they're subject to license.","start":6251.158,"stop":6256.292,"duration":5.13},{"text":"And that's the only question that was the issue in the case whether they should -- whether they should apply for a license and secure a license to operate.","start":6256.292,"stop":6263.987,"duration":7.69},{"text":"Now, if as it's contended, they couldn't get a license because of 28-31.1, then it would be their prerogative to come into the federal courts and say they were -- we were interfering with interstate commerce.","start":6263.987,"stop":6286.999,"duration":23.01}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument, Part 1: Parmelee Transportation Company v. Atchison, Topeka & Santa Fe Railway Company - March 06, 1958 (104)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/15576","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 189, Milton Knapp versus Mitchell D. Schweitzer et al.","start":0,"stop":18.199,"duration":18.2},{"text":"I -- I beg your pardon.","start":18.199,"stop":19.155,"duration":0.96},{"text":"Yes, I beg your pardon.","start":19.155,"stop":20.177,"duration":1.02},{"text":"I -- I skipped.","start":20.177,"stop":22.136,"duration":1.96},{"text":"Once again, Number 104, Parmelee Transportation Company versus Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway.","start":22.136,"stop":30.384,"duration":8.25},{"text":"I beg your --","start":30.384,"stop":30.499,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice.","start":30.499,"stop":31.244,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon.","start":31.244,"stop":32.927,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":32.927,"stop":35.741,"duration":2.81},{"text":"I currently appear here in the role of the devil's advocate after what both parties have been saying about Parmelee.","start":35.741,"stop":43.108,"duration":7.37},{"text":"The appeal in petition for certiorari in Number 104, throw out of the judgment which was rendered by the Court of Appeals of the Seventh Circuit.","start":43.108,"stop":52.558,"duration":9.45}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is this -- is this going to take an hour to recite after what we've gone through?","start":52.558,"stop":56.719,"duration":4.16}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I must say that our position is very different from the cities and I can say that it need not take any time at all if the Court's position is that there's no contest between the -- between Parmelee and the City.","start":56.719,"stop":69.906,"duration":13.19},{"text":"I would merely suggest that if the case is moot, the Court ought to vacate the judgments below and for the reason of mootness.","start":69.906,"stop":79.887,"duration":9.98}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Mootness is part of that?","start":79.887,"stop":81.76,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this bring the -- one of the questions that the Court has asked us to appear on.","start":81.76,"stop":87.486,"duration":5.73},{"text":"The problem is whether Parmelee has standing to maintain its position in this Court.","start":87.486,"stop":95.405,"duration":7.92},{"text":"Now, if Your Honor's question goes to whether the statute affects Parmelee or not that is not an issue in this case.","start":95.405,"stop":102.866,"duration":7.46},{"text":"We appear not against the City but on the side of the City.","start":102.866,"stop":108.515,"duration":5.65},{"text":"We have conceded that our operations which include both interterminal operations and transportation of passengers from the terminals to other points within the area defined by the -- the municipal ordinance are subject to the City's licensing power.","start":108.515,"stop":124.887,"duration":16.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What was your position?","start":124.887,"stop":127.692,"duration":2.8},{"text":"What kind of authority if you were a party in the lower court?","start":127.692,"stop":132.323,"duration":4.63}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"We appeared -- we intervened as a party.","start":132.323,"stop":134.943,"duration":2.62},{"text":"Our intervention was granted as permissive intervention although we sought it as intervention as of right.","start":134.943,"stop":141.403,"duration":6.46},{"text":"We contend that our interest as a competitor of Transfer would be adversely affected by any judgment which might be secured by Transfer in this action.","start":141.403,"stop":153.224,"duration":11.82},{"text":"In short, our position is that we have standing under the doctrine of the Frost case.","start":153.224,"stop":162.201,"duration":8.98},{"text":"Please the Court.","start":162.201,"stop":162.738,"duration":0.54},{"text":"I will --","start":162.738,"stop":163.389,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you going to argue that or leave it on the brief?","start":163.389,"stop":166.487,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"I will argue it if the Court preferred to argue it.","start":166.487,"stop":169.534,"duration":3.05},{"text":"If the Court prefers -- prefers to leave it to the brief, I will be glad to do so.","start":169.534,"stop":172.699,"duration":3.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's your judgment to control.","start":172.699,"stop":174.246,"duration":1.55},{"text":"I'm just wondering whether you think it's -- it's a seriously (Inaudible) question as it is and I for once should like to hear.","start":174.246,"stop":184.94,"duration":10.69},{"text":"If you think the Frost case controlled it economically.","start":184.94,"stop":187.571,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I think the Frost case does control it.","start":187.571,"stop":193.062,"duration":5.49},{"text":"There is one other question about the appealability of this case and this is a question whether an appeal rely under Section 1254 (2) from a judgment of a Court of Appeals holding a state statute unconstitutional.","start":193.062,"stop":209.245,"duration":16.18},{"text":"That is whether this is a final judgment for purposes of the appeal.","start":209.245,"stop":213.523,"duration":4.28},{"text":"My position maybe stated fairly shortly.","start":213.523,"stop":217.683,"duration":4.16},{"text":"We contend first that 1254 (2) ought not to and it was not intended to impose a final judgment requirement.","start":217.683,"stop":228.129,"duration":10.45},{"text":"This Court has held, I will concede, on two points that a final judgment requirement is in the statute.","start":228.129,"stop":234.459,"duration":6.33},{"text":"We set forth in our brief the fact that the Court did so without the benefit of argument of counsel.","start":234.459,"stop":243.067,"duration":8.61},{"text":"If it so, first in the Slaker case, shortly after the adoption of the 1925 Judiciary Act.","start":243.067,"stop":254.187,"duration":11.12},{"text":"And again, in the South Carolina Electric and Gas Company case relying on the Slaker case, that the Slaker case statement of a requirement for finality was a dictum because as Mr. Justice McReynolds said in rendering the opinion for the Court, the petition -- the petition in the court below contained three counts, none of which questioned the validity of a state statute.","start":254.187,"stop":278.643,"duration":24.46},{"text":"He then went on to state in his opinion that the appeal must be one from a final judgment.","start":278.643,"stop":284.884,"duration":6.24},{"text":"But again in reaching that conclusion, he relied on two cases.","start":284.884,"stop":288.821,"duration":3.94},{"text":"The first of which was an appeal from the Philippines Supreme Court in which the statute specifically made a requirement of finality.","start":288.821,"stop":296.763,"duration":7.94},{"text":"Now, the second was Collins against Miller which was a direct appeal from the -- from a District Court of United States with the statute also that made a specific requirement of finality.","start":296.763,"stop":308.478,"duration":11.72},{"text":"Now, the statute in question was adopted on the -- it was -- the section question was inserted in the Florida Senate when the 1925 Act was there.","start":308.478,"stop":321.294,"duration":12.82},{"text":"It was adopted from the provision authorizing appeal to this Court from state courts holding a federal statute unconstitutional.","start":321.294,"stop":331.741,"duration":10.45},{"text":"That provision specifically made a requirement of finality.Despite that, the -- and with this in front of them, the Congress adopted all the -- adopted all the remainder of the language but did not include within this statute any specifications of finality.","start":331.741,"stop":353.377,"duration":21.64},{"text":"There is so far as this Court's jurisdiction is concerned as you know no other provision in this -- in the code which requires a final judgment in terms of the Court -- review of the Courts of Appeals whether that review is by way of appeal or by way of certiorari.","start":353.377,"stop":371.489,"duration":18.11},{"text":"We suggest that there may be a good reason for that distinction and one of those is that the Court of Appeals does not get jurisdiction in the case until a final judgment has been entered by a District Court.","start":371.489,"stop":389.752,"duration":18.26},{"text":"I would submit that the type of question which is brought up under 1254 (2) is one of great importance.","start":389.752,"stop":397.312,"duration":7.56},{"text":"It involves the relationships of the state and federal government and will not present an issue to the Court until a United States Court of Appeals has first held a state statute unconstitutional that the reason behind this statute is the same as the reason behind the statute authorizing this Court to take jurisdiction by direct appeal in cases where the Federal Government, a statute of Federal Government is held unconstitutional in the Court of Appeals plus the additional factor with delicacy of the relationships between the two jurisdictions.","start":397.312,"stop":434.202,"duration":36.89},{"text":"And I would suggest that reading the intent of Congress, reading the purpose behind the Act and recognizing that this case is a comparatively few in number so that they will not likely to be a burden to the Court or that if they were, the Court could dispose them as they did in Slaker in the event of a frivolous appeal by assessing a penalty or by the usual method which it has adopted from time to time and that is by dismissing or rather in this event affirming per curiam.","start":434.202,"stop":467.014,"duration":32.81},{"text":"I would like to suggest in a minute or two that remains that even if the -- your final judgment requirement is in Section 1254 (2) of the statute, we meet that final judgment requirement in this case.","start":467.014,"stop":480.087,"duration":13.07},{"text":"The Court has stated a test whether a judgment is final is whether the -- the judgment below had terminated the litigation.","start":480.087,"stop":489.952,"duration":9.87},{"text":"So, if this Court were to affirm, nothing more it needs to be done on the remand and that's exactly the situation that this Court finds that this case is in","start":489.952,"stop":500.447,"duration":10.5},{"text":"Both parties have agreed.","start":500.447,"stop":502.401,"duration":1.95},{"text":"Both parties to this litigation that this judgment disposes of -- the judgment of the Court of Appeals, disposes all the issues between the parties that on remand, nothing would be left to be done in the event of affirmance or indeed in the event of a reversal, except to enter the judgment of the Court.","start":502.401,"stop":521.937,"duration":19.54},{"text":"That being so, we submit that we meet the test which this Court has from time to time suggested as stating the requirement of finality.","start":521.937,"stop":537.061,"duration":15.12},{"text":"If I may then in the -- with respect to the contested issues in the case or perhaps before I get to the contested issues, I should say that the -- there are certain concessions of both parties in this lawsuit which eliminate contest.","start":537.061,"stop":556.659,"duration":19.6},{"text":"The -- should I stop at this point, Your Honor or --","start":556.659,"stop":562.354,"duration":5.7}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"When the red light comes, Mr. Kurland.","start":562.354,"stop":566.062,"duration":3.71}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"The appellant has conceded that the City of Chicago has no power to impose economic regulations on the carrier -- carriage in question that as we do not claim for the City of Chicago, the authority to make the determination as to whether or not additional competition is or is not desirable.","start":566.062,"stop":591.874,"duration":25.81}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, we'll recess Mr. --","start":591.874,"stop":597.547,"duration":5.67}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument, Part 2: Parmelee Transportation Company v. Atchison, Topeka & Santa Fe Railway Company - March 06, 1958 (104)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/15575","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Kurland, you may proceed.","start":0,"stop":10.555,"duration":10.56}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":10.555,"stop":12.95,"duration":2.39},{"text":"Perhaps I'd better clarify our position that Parmelee stands in, particularly with relation to Section 28-31.1 of the Municipal Code.","start":12.95,"stop":24.506,"duration":11.56},{"text":"Mr. Grossman apparently contended that the statute -- the ordinance was valid but not applicable.","start":24.506,"stop":32.908,"duration":8.4},{"text":"The appellants here appear to have contended that it was applicable but invalid.","start":32.908,"stop":40.147,"duration":7.24},{"text":"And it's our position that it's both valid and applicable.","start":40.147,"stop":44.915,"duration":4.77}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The position it did what was?","start":44.915,"stop":46.253,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"That this ordinance -- Section 28-31.1 is both applicable and valid and applicable to transfer as we have no question in this case as to whether it's applicable for Parmelee.","start":46.253,"stop":61.38,"duration":15.13},{"text":"The Parmelee --","start":61.38,"stop":62.017,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"No question.","start":62.017,"stop":62.574,"duration":0.56},{"text":"It's -- it is plain (Inaudible).","start":62.574,"stop":65.915,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"We have never raised any question as -- so far as Parmelee is concerned.","start":65.915,"stop":69.553,"duration":3.64},{"text":"We do not do so here and this would not be the proper litigation to do so.","start":69.553,"stop":73.754,"duration":4.2},{"text":"Our position is that we have aligned ourselves with the City in defending the application and validity of these arguments.","start":73.754,"stop":82.725,"duration":8.97}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"But we can assume that Parmelee is the beneficiary on the renewal of the provision.","start":82.725,"stop":88.753,"duration":6.03}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"It's true that -- that Parmelee does have vehicle licenses at the moment.","start":88.753,"stop":94.736,"duration":5.98},{"text":"The renewal provision is not peculiar to this portion of the statute.","start":94.736,"stop":98.539,"duration":3.8},{"text":"It's applicable both to the delivery and the taxicab provisions but it's merely a form for administering a -- a statute to this point.","start":98.539,"stop":111.542,"duration":13},{"text":"It would be unfortunate and impractical to require carriers who have applied for and secured a license to come back year after year to renew their applications.","start":111.542,"stop":122.859,"duration":11.32},{"text":"And if terminal should apply for license and secure it, it will no longer have to apply for a license thereafter so long as it continues to comply with the terms of the statute.","start":122.859,"stop":138.64,"duration":15.78}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But under this ordinance to -- do the taxicab companies transport passengers from one station to another, are they obliged to take out this particular license?","start":138.64,"stop":152.998,"duration":14.36}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"No, because they are taking out another license under the same ordinance.","start":152.998,"stop":155.204,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes -- yes.","start":155.204,"stop":156.509,"duration":1.3},{"text":"So they're not -- it isn't applicable to them.","start":156.509,"stop":159.843,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"No, this -- this ordinance will be applicable only to terminal vehicles which are --","start":159.843,"stop":163.673,"duration":3.83}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":163.673,"stop":164.302,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"-- on the terms of the statute vehicles which pick up passengers at stations and deliver them --","start":164.302,"stop":168.822,"duration":4.52}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":168.822,"stop":169.012,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"-- within the central area.","start":169.012,"stop":172.004,"duration":2.99}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And is it true that there was only one license outstanding?","start":172.004,"stop":176.226,"duration":4.22}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"That Parmelee had all the licenses outstanding at the time of the passengers are --","start":176.226,"stop":180.925,"duration":4.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The only license -- the only license outstanding, was that a problem?","start":180.925,"stop":183.238,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":183.238,"stop":183.997,"duration":0.76},{"text":"And --","start":183.997,"stop":184.025,"duration":0.03}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If it's true and I suppose you would say that makes no difference.","start":184.025,"stop":187.596,"duration":3.57}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the statute -- the ordinance at the time specified that a terminal vehicle was a vehicle operated by a person who had a contract with the railroad.","start":187.596,"stop":199.589,"duration":11.99},{"text":"It's the railroad that gives the exclusive contract and not the City.","start":199.589,"stop":204.06,"duration":4.47},{"text":"The railroad had granted an exclusive contract to Parmelee.","start":204.06,"stop":209.335,"duration":5.28},{"text":"After the end of the Parmelee contract, when the railroads decided to hire another carrier, the crew in -- in response to a question Mr. Justice Harlan said earlier today, the City -- the City was asked to broaden the definition of terminal vehicles so that Parmelee could continue to operate.","start":209.335,"stop":236.103,"duration":26.77},{"text":"Under the 28-31.1, Parmelee is now required to have a license and can continue to have a license.","start":236.103,"stop":243.836,"duration":7.73},{"text":"A terminal can also apply for a license and we submit and can secure one if they meet the conditions which the City imposes.","start":243.836,"stop":252.029,"duration":8.19},{"text":"There is no monopoly situation involved here with the Court.","start":252.029,"stop":256.857,"duration":4.83}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Under -- under the tariffs filed by the railroad, today, tomorrow include other terminal vehicle enterprises?","start":256.857,"stop":267.549,"duration":10.69}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry, sir.","start":267.549,"stop":269.076,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the tariffs which the railroads have filed with the Interstate Commerce Commission --","start":269.076,"stop":273.836,"duration":4.76}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"They certainly --","start":273.836,"stop":273.982,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- today or tomorrow or could they -- the day after this complaint was filed have given their patronage to other --","start":273.982,"stop":284.497,"duration":10.51}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"They certainly could subject to cost to the lawsuit they might in fact be terminal.","start":284.497,"stop":288.132,"duration":3.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm not talking about that.","start":288.132,"stop":289.228,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":289.228,"stop":289.725,"duration":0.5},{"text":"Their power under the statute certainly exists for them to retain another service.","start":289.725,"stop":296.769,"duration":7.04},{"text":"Let me point it out that the service which terminal is supplying is not an agency service as it's been suggested.","start":296.769,"stop":306.017,"duration":9.25},{"text":"Under the terms of the contract between terminals and the railroads, terminal is acting as an independent contractor.","start":306.017,"stop":316.754,"duration":10.74},{"text":"They're required to act as an independent contractor.","start":316.754,"stop":319.227,"duration":2.47},{"text":"On page 40, the bottom of the page in Section 11 after the contract, it is specifically provided that the transfer shall be and remain an independent contractor.","start":319.227,"stop":333.862,"duration":14.64},{"text":"And if you will look at the top of that page, you will find another provision of the contract which indicated quite clearly that it was a contemplation of the parties that this transfer service would submit itself to the rules and regulations of government agencies having jurisdiction over it.","start":333.862,"stop":355.417,"duration":21.55},{"text":"At the top of the page in (l) of paragraph 10 of the contract between the railroads and terminals -- I'm sorry, in Transfer, if the agreement provides that Transfer shall comply at all times with all laws, rules and regulations of governmental agencies having jurisdiction over it.","start":355.417,"stop":374.889,"duration":19.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Are the tariffs by -- are the tariffs of these railroads in the record?","start":374.889,"stop":380.631,"duration":5.74},{"text":"Or can you tell us whether in the tariffs filed including this absorbed shuttling service formally and previously and now Transfer was specifically mentioned.","start":380.631,"stop":392.822,"duration":12.19}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"They are not, sir.","start":392.822,"stop":393.449,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They're not.","start":393.449,"stop":394.156,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"They are in the record with the -- at page 195 of the record.","start":394.156,"stop":398.745,"duration":4.59},{"text":"You will find the tariff.","start":398.745,"stop":402.096,"duration":3.35},{"text":"It starts on page 193.","start":402.096,"stop":404.871,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So that all the railroads does is to include this as the -- the true rate --","start":404.871,"stop":411.915,"duration":7.04}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly, sir.","start":411.915,"stop":412.492,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- transaction.","start":412.492,"stop":413.568,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"This is a choice of the railroads.","start":413.568,"stop":419.065,"duration":5.5},{"text":"The position that we maintain here is that unless and until Transfer shall have applied for a license and have had it refused on improper grounds, they lack the standing to complain about the action of the City of Chicago.","start":419.065,"stop":438.748,"duration":19.68},{"text":"It has been their choice to avoid making use of the administrator of remedies that are available to them.","start":438.748,"stop":446.729,"duration":7.98},{"text":"We concede --","start":446.729,"stop":447.755,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":447.755,"stop":451.945,"duration":4.19}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"So the question is whether there's an unconstitutional requirement on this phase, Your Honor.","start":451.945,"stop":456.863,"duration":4.92},{"text":"And they take the position of this because the statute contains -- the ordinance contains the words \"convenience and necessity\" or \"certificate of convenience and necessity.\"","start":456.863,"stop":465.743,"duration":8.88},{"text":"It's quite clear from both decisions of this Court and decisions of the Illinois court that that phrase is not a phrase at all.","start":465.743,"stop":475.16,"duration":9.42},{"text":"It is not restricted to the application of economic considerations.","start":475.16,"stop":480.727,"duration":5.57},{"text":"We concede that if it were, the City could not exercise its power over the -- the transport company.","start":480.727,"stop":488.759,"duration":8.03},{"text":"Now, the fact of the matter is that in the cases which have been before this Court, the Court has recognized and permitted states to regulate the carriers, motor carriers over the highways of the state under a requirement that they obtain a “certificate of convenience and necessity”.","start":488.759,"stop":512.856,"duration":24.1},{"text":"If I may, I'd like to make reference to the case of Columbia Terminals Company against Lambert which is exactly an off-course with this particular case.","start":512.856,"stop":523.897,"duration":11.04},{"text":"In both cases, we had interstate commerce involved.","start":523.897,"stop":527.969,"duration":4.07},{"text":"In both cases, the interstate commerce involved was a transfer between railroad terminals.","start":527.969,"stop":535.893,"duration":7.92},{"text":"In both cases, the state required that the carrier apply for a license in order to engage in the service.","start":535.893,"stop":544.371,"duration":8.48},{"text":"In both cases, the state -- the carrier refused to apply for that license.","start":544.371,"stop":552.275,"duration":7.9},{"text":"In both cases, the counsel for the state asserted that the state was without power to apply these economic tests, those tests which were rejected in Buck against Kuykendall.","start":552.275,"stop":566.958,"duration":14.68},{"text":"The state was without power to apply those tests to an interstate motor carrier.","start":566.958,"stop":572.11,"duration":5.15},{"text":"Now, the Court in that case held that the carrier was not eligible to complain about the constitutionality of the statute until such time as they had first applied for a license and had it refused on improper grounds.","start":572.11,"stop":591.71,"duration":19.6},{"text":"Perhaps, I should also make reference to the case of Bradley against Public Utilities Commission of Ohio.","start":591.71,"stop":602.462,"duration":10.75},{"text":"I do so because the Buck and Kuykendall case as you may recall is written by Mr. Justice Brandeis so to as the Bradley against Public Utilities case.","start":602.462,"stop":612.953,"duration":10.49},{"text":"The Public Utilities case came after the Buck and Kuykendall case.","start":612.953,"stop":617.791,"duration":4.84},{"text":"In that case, in the Bradley case, the Court was asked to decide whether a state could impose a requirement for securing a certificate of public convenience and necessity to an interstate motor carrier.","start":617.791,"stop":634.312,"duration":16.52},{"text":"The Court held that it could do so, so long as the grounds which -- on which it was applying that statute were grounds relevant to the police power and the power to control the highways.","start":634.312,"stop":647.676,"duration":13.36},{"text":"We submit that that's exactly what we have in this situation.","start":647.676,"stop":653.913,"duration":6.24},{"text":"The Supreme Court of Illinois as I have said in the Yellow Cab Company against City of Chicago --","start":653.913,"stop":660.278,"duration":6.37}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Kurland, you make no distinction between the -- the public necessity and convenient provision of the ordinance and the other ones that counsel referred to as -- as police regulations.","start":660.278,"stop":675.346,"duration":15.07}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":675.346,"stop":675.416,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think they're subject to any distinction of any kind?","start":675.416,"stop":678.3,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"Do I think they're --","start":678.3,"stop":679.009,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":679.009,"stop":679.197,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"I think they are not, sir.","start":679.197,"stop":680.552,"duration":1.36},{"text":"I think that they are both the -- the first set or more specific that this has given some discretion in the exercise of the granting of the license in terms of the police power.","start":680.552,"stop":693.641,"duration":13.09},{"text":"And if I may revert to the Bradley case and I must use a hypothetical because in the absence of the application for a license, I don't know, nobody knows what the position the license commissioner would take on this.","start":693.641,"stop":707.054,"duration":13.41},{"text":"But suppose that the application for the license were denied or were granted on condition as it -- as it could be granted under this provision on condition that the terminal vehicles not use certain streets during the rush hour in the Chicago loop that they reroute their vehicles during that period.","start":707.054,"stop":731.002,"duration":23.95},{"text":"Nowhere else in the ordinance would that probably be available to the -- to the City.","start":731.002,"stop":738.287,"duration":7.29},{"text":"I submit that it is available under 28-31.1.","start":738.287,"stop":743.644,"duration":5.36},{"text":"In short, my suggestion is the fact that the City has attempted to impose police power regulations on what is admittedly interstate commerce does not invalidate the statute.","start":743.644,"stop":757.068,"duration":13.42},{"text":"And until such time as the application has been made to the City, we do not know that the license will be denied.","start":757.068,"stop":765.923,"duration":8.86},{"text":"We do not know that if it's denied, it will be denied on the improper grounds.","start":765.923,"stop":770.328,"duration":4.4},{"text":"And so we pull in a long line of cases not the -- perhaps the most recent statement of this Court on the subject based on the Public Utilities Commission of California against United States handed down on Monday in which the Court said \"If an administrative proceeding might leave no room until the constitutional question, the administrator for Parmelee plainly should be pursued.\"","start":770.328,"stop":792.851,"duration":22.52},{"text":"And that's all that we suggest should be done here until such time as it is preserved.","start":792.851,"stop":798.695,"duration":5.84},{"text":"This fraud is faced with a hypothetical question.","start":798.695,"stop":798.821,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But it did -- it didn't follow -- it didn't act that way in that case, did it?","start":798.821,"stop":804.889,"duration":6.07}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":804.889,"stop":804.957,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"It turned out the other way.","start":804.957,"stop":805.753,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":805.753,"stop":806.352,"duration":0.6},{"text":"The -- the proposition there goes back to the -- the Court took the position that the statute was invalid on its face just as it did in the Georgia case to which Justice Whittaker referred earlier today.","start":806.352,"stop":821.72,"duration":15.37},{"text":"The only basis for saying that this statute is invalid on its face is by construing convenience and necessity to allow the City to impose invalid economic requirements, requirements which would be invalid under the Buck and Kuykendall test.","start":821.72,"stop":839.385,"duration":17.66}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask this?","start":839.385,"stop":842.796,"duration":3.41},{"text":"Is there any distinction between this case in the -- in the Bradley case in that -- in this case not only as a finding of public convenience and necessity required but also after that there must be a political decision as to whether it will be granted to that party by the City Council?","start":842.796,"stop":866.047,"duration":23.25}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, you -- you say it's a political decision and it has been suggested that it would be with the City Council as a body which has administrative functions as well as legislative functions in the City of Chicago.","start":866.047,"stop":877.433,"duration":11.39},{"text":"Now, I don't know if this Court has ever suggested that the administrative procedure, the form of the administrative procedure should take within a jurisdiction shall be governed by the -- the determination of this Court.","start":877.433,"stop":890.203,"duration":12.77},{"text":"Again, we cannot tell how formal or informal the requirement of going before the City Council is going to be until such time as the application has been made.","start":890.203,"stop":903.804,"duration":13.6}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What I was saying -- there's one -- it might be one thing for the -- the City to say that anybody seeking such a license was established if there's a public necessity for it and that there must be a finding to that effect.","start":903.804,"stop":924.616,"duration":20.81},{"text":"But I think there's an added element, isn't there when they say even after that has been found that it then rest with a body in its discretion as to whether it will be granted.","start":924.616,"stop":939.125,"duration":14.51},{"text":"Now, I -- I don't know that that -- was there such an element in the Bradley case?","start":939.125,"stop":943.423,"duration":4.3}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"No, there was not, sir.","start":943.423,"stop":944.748,"duration":1.33},{"text":"They had a Public Utility Commission.","start":944.748,"stop":946.255,"duration":1.51},{"text":"But I think that the position was quite specifically.","start":946.255,"stop":951.983,"duration":5.73},{"text":"The analogy was well drawn this morning when the suggestion was made that the Commissioner is acting as an examiner, a finder of fact to make the determination and recommend action by the City Council.","start":951.983,"stop":963.505,"duration":11.52},{"text":"Now clearly, if we had -- if the City Council were to put on a different set of hats and designate itself to Public Utility Commission for the City of Chicago, we would have a similar situation to the Bradley case.","start":963.505,"stop":977.945,"duration":14.44},{"text":"It's the fact that they happen to have in addition to their legislative capacities.","start":977.945,"stop":982.903,"duration":4.96},{"text":"They have undertaken an administrative function.","start":982.903,"stop":987.095,"duration":4.19},{"text":"I do not see how that sanction of function by the City Council makes for a basis for distinguishing the Bradley case.","start":987.095,"stop":997.665,"duration":10.57}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"As I understood Mr. Mathews, he contended that under 302 (c) (2), the Congress has authorized the railroads themselves to choose an agent either by -- by contract such as to do the specific work, kind of work.","start":997.665,"stop":1020.92,"duration":23.25},{"text":"If that interpretation is accepted, would you still say that they could be revised --","start":1020.92,"stop":1026.617,"duration":5.7}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"No, this -- this would go to a separate issue.","start":1026.617,"stop":1028.9,"duration":2.28},{"text":"The point that I've been talking to is the power of the City to -- to regulate interstate commerce in the exercise of its police power.","start":1028.9,"stop":1038.05,"duration":9.15}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Which you already had presented.","start":1038.05,"stop":1039.039,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, yes.","start":1039.039,"stop":1039.728,"duration":0.69},{"text":"Now, we are now -- in the suggestion that you raised goes to the question of conflict with the federal statute if there is any and it's our position that there is no conflict with the federal statute.","start":1039.728,"stop":1051.894,"duration":12.17},{"text":"The federal statute was interpreted by the Interstate Commerce Commission itself with regard to the very tight -- with the very activity that's under question in this case.","start":1051.894,"stop":1065.496,"duration":13.6},{"text":"In -- in the case of status of Parmelee, subsequent to the passage of the statute which has been referred to.","start":1065.496,"stop":1074.146,"duration":8.65}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What page is that?","start":1074.146,"stop":1074.164,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"And on status of -- it's on page 39 of our brief.","start":1074.164,"stop":1079.841,"duration":5.68},{"text":"It starts on 38.","start":1079.841,"stop":1081.286,"duration":1.45},{"text":"The quotation is found at 38 and 39.","start":1081.286,"stop":1085.298,"duration":4.01},{"text":"The Interstate Commerce Commission initiated a proceeding to determine whether or not the certain action should -- whether any action should be taken for purposes of issuing orders with reference to Parmelee.","start":1085.298,"stop":1100.287,"duration":14.99},{"text":"Parmelee was then engaged in the service of transferring passengers from one terminal to another under contract with the railroads exactly as -- as Transfer is doing now.","start":1100.287,"stop":1112.931,"duration":12.64},{"text":"The Court held or the Interstate Commerce Commission held, first, that they were not motor carriers for purposes of Part 2 of the Act and we're not subject to regulation there.","start":1112.931,"stop":1125.738,"duration":12.81},{"text":"They held that under Part 1 of the Act, they were subject to regulation although they were not carriers under Part 1 of the Act.","start":1125.738,"stop":1133.775,"duration":8.04},{"text":"The Court -- the Commission specifically makes the statement.","start":1133.775,"stop":1136.798,"duration":3.02},{"text":"They are not a carrier but they are subject to regulation under the Act.","start":1136.798,"stop":1141.556,"duration":4.76},{"text":"The fact of the matter is that the Interstate Commerce Commission has never issued any regulation or attempted to assert any power over this type of activity.","start":1141.556,"stop":1151.955,"duration":10.4},{"text":"It's an activity which again as I've stated in the status of Parmelee, the railroads can adopt or reject at their will.","start":1151.955,"stop":1160.487,"duration":8.53},{"text":"But as in -- in many cities, they do have this transfer service.","start":1160.487,"stop":1163.91,"duration":3.42},{"text":"In many cities, they do not have this transfer service.","start":1163.91,"stop":1166.565,"duration":2.65}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"If they do, however, make a contract, how can anyone else require them to be anything more than to survive by this Act here --","start":1166.565,"stop":1181.379,"duration":14.81}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":1181.379,"stop":1181.898,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- based on their qualifications?","start":1181.898,"stop":1185.012,"duration":3.11},{"text":"If -- if they have made the railroad eligible, Congress has made the railroads eligible --","start":1185.012,"stop":1190.954,"duration":5.94}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"The statute does not say that.It says that they -- that they have the power to engage in this activity.","start":1190.954,"stop":1196.462,"duration":5.51}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, the railroads too.","start":1196.462,"stop":1198.057,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1198.057,"stop":1198.644,"duration":0.59},{"text":"And they can engage in this activity.","start":1198.644,"stop":1201.007,"duration":2.36},{"text":"But the Congress has not suggests that the agents which they choose need not to comply with the police regulations of the states.","start":1201.007,"stop":1209.97,"duration":8.96}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But will they have to on the --","start":1209.97,"stop":1211.068,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let me -- let me, if I may, sir, point out that the -- the very -- the railroads themselves in this case are taking the position that the other provisions of this ordinance are applicable to Transfer that they do have to apply for a license, that they do have to meet the safety requirements which is specifically set forth in those parts of the ordinance prior to Section 28-31.1 and that they're to subject suspension if they do not comply with those regulations.","start":1211.068,"stop":1247.579,"duration":36.51},{"text":"Now, the -- the Interstate Commerce Commission has indicated that it is true not with regards to the specific activity but with reference to activities of motor carriers within a municipal area.","start":1247.579,"stop":1264.679,"duration":17.1},{"text":"The -- the Interstate Commerce Commission itself has rules as to require the submission of these local carriers operating within this area to local police regulations.","start":1264.679,"stop":1280.955,"duration":16.28},{"text":"They make certain exceptions which are not pertinent here except the carriers of explosives for the reason which I do not think of is relevant.","start":1280.955,"stop":1293.603,"duration":12.65},{"text":"But the fact of the matter is that there is no indication either in the statute and there is certainly has no indication by the way the Commission has acted that the federal government either has undertaken, is prepared to undertake the things it was to undertake this type of municipal activity within a single municipal area.","start":1293.603,"stop":1314.598,"duration":20.99}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But if Congress has said they can function that way, whatever right the City might have to punish them for some violation of law, can it say they cannot function if Congress had said they can?","start":1314.598,"stop":1329.489,"duration":14.89}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"The Congress has not said that they must function or can't function by choosing a -- a transfer service which would be operating in violation of the law.","start":1329.489,"stop":1341.723,"duration":12.23},{"text":"Now, it's been suggested that what we're talking about is a recent decision of this Court in Castle against Hayes Freight Company.","start":1341.723,"stop":1348.976,"duration":7.25},{"text":"We are conceded in our brief and we concede constantly throughout this litigation that the federal or government if it had issued a license or if the federal regulations came into conflict with the regulations of this ordinance then it would be quite clear and nobody challenges the supremacy of the federal government in this area.","start":1348.976,"stop":1370.738,"duration":21.76}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And you are saying that this statute, whatever it does, does not of itself automatically allow railroads to operate this kind of business in Chicago.","start":1370.738,"stop":1381.635,"duration":10.9}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"It does not allow them to --","start":1381.635,"stop":1383.412,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It does not automatically guarantee that they should be allowed.","start":1383.412,"stop":1386.434,"duration":3.02}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1386.434,"stop":1386.911,"duration":0.48},{"text":"It does not give the equivalent of a certificate of convenience and necessity which did exist in the Hayes case.","start":1386.911,"stop":1395.088,"duration":8.18},{"text":"What we would have would be if we were to analogize this to the Hayes case, Hayes to retain an independent contractor to carry on some of its business and then tell the State of Illinois that it has no power over this independent contractor for the reason that Hayes -- not the independent contractor but Hayes has a certificate of convenience and necessity (Voice Overlap) --","start":1395.088,"stop":1417.745,"duration":22.66}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But if the Congress has said that Hayes could do it --","start":1417.745,"stop":1420.907,"duration":3.16}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"I have no --","start":1420.907,"stop":1421.284,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- independent contractors.","start":1421.284,"stop":1422.831,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, we would -- have no question about that.","start":1422.831,"stop":1424.897,"duration":2.07},{"text":"There's no language -- nothing in the statute indicated what Congress did.","start":1424.897,"stop":1428.58,"duration":3.68},{"text":"And certainly, the action of the Interstate Commerce Commission would indicate that the federal government just kept a hands-off policy over this type of operation.","start":1428.58,"stop":1436.813,"duration":8.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I haven't read the series of Parmelee into 288 I.C.C.","start":1436.813,"stop":1440.923,"duration":4.11},{"text":"So I'm just going to ask you what that decide or doesn't decide.","start":1440.923,"stop":1446.24,"duration":5.32},{"text":"Did I understand you to say that the Commission could exercise but has not chosen to exercise power over Parmelee in that litigation?","start":1446.24,"stop":1459.521,"duration":13.28}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1459.521,"stop":1460.908,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What kind of -- what kind of exercise of power would they have?","start":1460.908,"stop":1466.258,"duration":5.35}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"I think they could exercise -- issue regulations governing the -- the operation of this part of Interstate Commerce the same as they have with regard and as the respondent's brief show, with regard to some of the trucking operations that are combined with (Voice Overlap) operation.","start":1466.258,"stop":1484.941,"duration":18.68}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I mean, deal with physical aspects.","start":1484.941,"stop":1487.963,"duration":3.02},{"text":"They actually --","start":1487.963,"stop":1489.119,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"They could --","start":1489.119,"stop":1489.436,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- vehicle, the type of vehicle and all that?","start":1489.436,"stop":1491.921,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"They could deal with safety with the employee -- with the hiring of employees, with the -- they -- they could cover all of the area but they have -- they had not said so and if -- if you're asking what they said in the Parmelee case this is what my interpretation of the Parmelee case.","start":1491.921,"stop":1505.784,"duration":13.86}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What was sought to be done by that proceeding?","start":1505.784,"stop":1508.916,"duration":3.13}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"It was sought to bring the Parmelee's operations under the active regulation of the -- of the Interstate Commerce Commission.","start":1508.916,"stop":1517.148,"duration":8.23},{"text":"Now, when you say sought to be done, I -- I can't answer that.","start":1517.148,"stop":1520.37,"duration":3.22},{"text":"They initiated this proceeding themselves.","start":1520.37,"stop":1521.795,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And then they dismissed it and ordered to continue on the proceeding will be entered.","start":1521.795,"stop":1525.418,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1525.418,"stop":1526.015,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what was the proceeding for?","start":1526.015,"stop":1528.059,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"To determine whether a certain regulation should be issued by the --","start":1528.059,"stop":1531.131,"duration":3.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Of a physical character or -- or the inter-contract relation between the railroad and the Parmelee?","start":1531.131,"stop":1539.989,"duration":8.86}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, you're asking me for motives which I --","start":1539.989,"stop":1544.63,"duration":4.64}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, I'm not asking for motives.","start":1544.63,"stop":1546.127,"duration":1.5},{"text":"I'm continuing the question put --","start":1546.127,"stop":1547.893,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":1547.893,"stop":1547.971,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- by Justice Black as to the extent, as to the extent of taking over by the Commission of aspects of this service.","start":1547.971,"stop":1559.5,"duration":11.53}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"I would suggest that power is playing around the situation.","start":1559.5,"stop":1563.011,"duration":3.51}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But you say that --","start":1563.011,"stop":1563.957,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"They have chosen not to exercise it.","start":1563.957,"stop":1566.452,"duration":2.49},{"text":"They have chosen not to exercise any of the power which they have over this type of operation.","start":1566.452,"stop":1571.93,"duration":5.48},{"text":"They found that it removed from this Part 2 of the Act.","start":1571.93,"stop":1576.649,"duration":4.72},{"text":"They established their power.","start":1576.649,"stop":1579.481,"duration":2.83},{"text":"They assert their power over this operation as a railroad operation but they deny that this is a carrier which I take it means that the Commerce Commission has the same power over this operation as they would have over railroad operations, any other form of railroad operation.","start":1579.481,"stop":1601.4,"duration":21.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll put --","start":1601.4,"stop":1601.61,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"If they chose to exercise it.","start":1601.61,"stop":1603.724,"duration":2.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll put to you another question whether anything in the filed tariff until it changed by the carriers from having free such terminal service and the answer -- your answer was yes --","start":1603.724,"stop":1618.968,"duration":15.24}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"That there is nothing in the tariff which would prevent them from engaging free such --","start":1618.968,"stop":1623.308,"duration":4.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"From having Transfer and also Parmelee now.","start":1623.308,"stop":1626.851,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1626.851,"stop":1628.139,"duration":1.29},{"text":"Let me suggest --","start":1628.139,"stop":1628.876,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I gathered from what you've said that if the Commission could choose to restrict that inter-terminal -- inter-terminal service to one such service carrier.","start":1628.876,"stop":1640.476,"duration":11.6},{"text":"Is that right?","start":1640.476,"stop":1641.023,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"I should think that it could, yes, Your Honor.","start":1641.023,"stop":1642.907,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And what you are saying is that this is one of those cases -- what was that case (Inaudible) he wrote, that the power is dormant and not being exercised, the police power can -- can move in that area until the Commission displaces it.","start":1642.907,"stop":1657.694,"duration":14.79}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":1657.694,"stop":1658.401,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's your position.","start":1658.401,"stop":1659.048,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it is.","start":1659.048,"stop":1660.593,"duration":1.55},{"text":"And so in -- in brief, our position is that we do not have an attempt to exercise economic control over the interstate commerce involved in this case nor do we have any conflict between the City's ordinance.","start":1660.593,"stop":1675.924,"duration":15.33},{"text":"I'm talking both cases on the face of the ordinance.","start":1675.924,"stop":1678.407,"duration":2.48},{"text":"We do not have any conflict between the ordinance and any federal regulation.","start":1678.407,"stop":1683.686,"duration":5.28},{"text":"That being so, this Court cannot be ask to make a decision as to what the City's powers are until they've been invoked.","start":1683.686,"stop":1691.282,"duration":7.6},{"text":"They have not been invoked and therefore, it seems to me that the railroads and the transport service are in no position at this time to ask this Court to pass on what is a hypothetical question.","start":1691.282,"stop":1706.822,"duration":15.54},{"text":"Thank you, Your Honor.","start":1706.822,"stop":1717.455,"duration":10.63}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Matthews.","start":1717.455,"stop":1719.132,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll try to be very brief.","start":1719.132,"stop":1722.453,"duration":3.32},{"text":"I won't take too long if I may.","start":1722.453,"stop":1728.888,"duration":6.43},{"text":"And perhaps I can save time by simply surrogate and following on the points the counsel has made.","start":1728.888,"stop":1736.588,"duration":7.7},{"text":"In the first place, counsel attempts to say that by reason of the fact that Transfer is what he calls an independent contractor that Section 202 (c) doesn't govern here.","start":1736.588,"stop":1754.837,"duration":18.25},{"text":"Well, now Section 202 (c) (2) says that it governs transportation by motor vehicle by any person whether as agent or under a contractual arrangement.","start":1754.837,"stop":1773.528,"duration":18.69},{"text":"Now, whatever else you can say about the contract between Transfer and the railroads which appears beginning at page 25 of the record.","start":1773.528,"stop":1790.358,"duration":16.83},{"text":"It's a long contract.","start":1790.358,"stop":1792.003,"duration":1.64},{"text":"It is a contractual arrangement but no question about that, so it is squarely within the terms of Section 202 (c) and you can't escape that by saying, \"Well, obviously if you have a written contract whereby you make somebody an independent contractor that nevertheless would mean it's a contractual arrangement.\"","start":1792.003,"stop":1814.161,"duration":22.16},{"text":"Now, the counsel has mentioned that the recent decision of this Court last Monday in the Public Utilities Commission of California against United States and perhaps I do not need to advert to that but it seems to me this one sentence that I would like to read fits this case perfectly on all of this talk about exhausting administrative remedies.","start":1814.161,"stop":1841.012,"duration":26.85},{"text":"And that is this, but where the only the question is whether it is constitutional to fasten the administrative procedure onto a litigant -- onto the litigant, the administrative agency may be defied and judicial relief sought as the only effective way of protecting the asserted constitutional right.","start":1841.012,"stop":1863.613,"duration":22.6},{"text":"That is precisely this case.","start":1863.613,"stop":1866.116,"duration":2.5},{"text":"And the Chief Justice says perfectly characterized this because after you get all through with your so-called administrative procedure, nevertheless, the Chicago City Council says you've got to come in and lobby us before you can operate.","start":1866.116,"stop":1886.548,"duration":20.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Matthews, may I ask you whether you think it will make a difference if instead of the Chicago City Council or the Commerce Commission of Illinois?","start":1886.548,"stop":1896.377,"duration":9.83}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1896.377,"stop":1897.246,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think it's a matter of conflict that makes a difference who the agency is that the state has chosen (Voice Overlap) --","start":1897.246,"stop":1905.738,"duration":8.49}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh well --","start":1905.738,"stop":1906.205,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- by the police power determination.","start":1906.205,"stop":1908.021,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm going to withdraw my answer and say no, sir, in this that the Commerce Commission of the State of Illinois would have no authority to say who shall engage in interstate commerce in Illinois.","start":1908.021,"stop":1923.435,"duration":15.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, nobody would.But my question is rather the suggestion which for practical purposes I'm ready to accept that considerations that may move the City Council, is that what it is?","start":1923.435,"stop":1937.637,"duration":14.2}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1937.637,"stop":1938.765,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The City Council of Chicago.","start":1938.765,"stop":1940.2,"duration":1.43},{"text":"I don't want to be discriminating or New York (Inaudible) whatnot.","start":1940.2,"stop":1945.529,"duration":5.33},{"text":"I want to know whether the Constitution would make a difference whether the State's choice of the agent in exercising as it claims its police power varied it because pursuit the agency that it has chosen is much more likely to be governed by political considerations than a supposedly judicial-minded administrative agency.","start":1945.529,"stop":1973.498,"duration":27.97},{"text":"Do you think this Court can say, \"Well, we know the City Council of Chicago will be guided by considerations,\" they're rather political where the Commerce Commission of Illinois would be guided by more or less objective considerations.","start":1973.498,"stop":1986.495,"duration":13},{"text":"Do you think we can take that -- take that line?","start":1986.495,"stop":1989.126,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know.","start":1989.126,"stop":1989.805,"duration":0.68},{"text":"And frankly, I've never thought of that but --","start":1989.805,"stop":1991.5,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's essential in this business.","start":1991.5,"stop":1993.863,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"But it is -- I -- I think -- I think you can be for this reason that public service commissions and regulatory commissions are traditionally governed by certain processes of -- of weighing the evidence and making findings of fact and so forth.","start":1993.863,"stop":2014.888,"duration":21.02},{"text":"And well, yes, I'll get warm up to this.","start":2014.888,"stop":2017.574,"duration":2.69},{"text":"I can see a lot of difference.","start":2017.574,"stop":2019.548,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I can see a lot of --","start":2019.548,"stop":2020.217,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"If the -- if the public utilities -- if the Public Utilities Commission of Illinois denies a certificate on constitutional grounds, the courts of Illinois can review that but the courts of Illinois cannot review the discretion of the Chicago City Council.","start":2020.217,"stop":2037.625,"duration":17.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Not if it's a discretion within the allowable area by which a body exercise discretion.","start":2037.625,"stop":2043.332,"duration":5.71},{"text":"That's equally true of the Board of Alderman or a City Council or administrative agency or whatever you call it.","start":2043.332,"stop":2049.128,"duration":5.8}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":2049.128,"stop":2050.635,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And who is this Court to tell Illinois or any other states who is likely to give objective judgment on a question within the state power?","start":2050.635,"stop":2062.847,"duration":12.21}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"If Your Honor please, I think the question -- I -- I think we don't need even to go into that for this reason.","start":2062.847,"stop":2068.803,"duration":5.96}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that -- that answer.","start":2068.803,"stop":2070.628,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"That the -- this Court has never held and in the long line of cases it has held to the contrary.","start":2070.628,"stop":2078.376,"duration":7.75},{"text":"This Court has always held that where a discretion to engage in interstate commerce as to who shall conduct the Commerce is vested in a state or in municipality every such regulation has been struck down by this Court.","start":2078.376,"stop":2097.06,"duration":18.68}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that proper issue but I do not understand that we can say, so that I can say, merely because I can take practical notice of the fact that a City Council is likely to be all political and I'm not that sure about that either.","start":2097.06,"stop":2111.531,"duration":14.47},{"text":"Then the administrative agency of the state that therefore the power vested in the City Council would be bad or it might be good if vested into the so-called \"administrative agency\".","start":2111.531,"stop":2123.727,"duration":12.2}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't think we need to go that far.","start":2123.727,"stop":2127.448,"duration":3.72}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right, I understand that answer.","start":2127.448,"stop":2136.56,"duration":9.11}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Now --","start":2136.56,"stop":2138.005,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"In Illinois, is there -- is there any review at all of the discretion of the City Council in adopting or rejecting ordinances?","start":2138.005,"stop":2149.444,"duration":11.44}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Not at the discretion.","start":2149.444,"stop":2150.47,"duration":1.03},{"text":"There is, of course, to review in the courts, their ordinary review of the validity whether the action is within the power of the City or whether it's constitutional.","start":2150.47,"stop":2158.957,"duration":8.49},{"text":"But --","start":2158.957,"stop":2159.327,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But -- but even assuming that -- that they have the right -- assuming they have the right to do it and the City Council denies -- denies the right by a refusal to pass an ordinance.","start":2159.327,"stop":2176.212,"duration":16.88},{"text":"Can there be any -- any review in the State of Illinois --","start":2176.212,"stop":2179.903,"duration":3.69}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2179.903,"stop":2180.62,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of such refusal?","start":2180.62,"stop":2182.345,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2182.345,"stop":2183.95,"duration":1.61},{"text":"You mean if the City Council just did nothing?","start":2183.95,"stop":2186.094,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if they just -- if they just said in spite of -- of a favorable ruling by the Commissioner on the necessity and public necessity and convenience, it said no by a vote of so many, so maybe -- so maybe won't -- we won't --","start":2186.094,"stop":2203.242,"duration":17.15}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely no reviews.","start":2203.242,"stop":2203.799,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- pass the ordinance.","start":2203.799,"stop":2204.745,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"You couldn't -- you couldn't mandamus the City Council to --","start":2204.745,"stop":2207.749,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Could there be any review.","start":2207.749,"stop":2208.657,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2208.657,"stop":2208.717,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, it would take the -- the ordinary Board of Commerce, Public Utilities or whatever it is.","start":2208.717,"stop":2216.61,"duration":7.89},{"text":"They're usually subject to some kind of judicial review as to whether they have abused their discretion and so forth, are they not?","start":2216.61,"stop":2224.806,"duration":8.2}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"They always are.","start":2224.806,"stop":2226.113,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But in Illinois, do you know whether the City Council hasn't licensing authority of all sorts of things?","start":2226.113,"stop":2234.335,"duration":8.22}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes.","start":2234.335,"stop":2235.6,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Cities of -- cities of United States have full of licensing powers in -- in City Council or the like.","start":2235.6,"stop":2241.788,"duration":6.19}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Unquestionable.","start":2241.788,"stop":2243.229,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The judicial review -- is there any difference between reviewing or withholding of a license for a wrong ground that in -- was deemed to be installed or I mean, vesting power, where the City Council or some other agencies that has licensing power, if there is review for arbitrary conduct.","start":2243.229,"stop":2260.313,"duration":17.08},{"text":"The City Council is amenable to such review as any other body.","start":2260.313,"stop":2263.736,"duration":3.42},{"text":"Isn't that true?","start":2263.736,"stop":2265.373,"duration":1.64},{"text":"It can't review.","start":2265.373,"stop":2266.321,"duration":0.95},{"text":"You can't review of course political authority.","start":2266.321,"stop":2269.534,"duration":3.21}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well (Voice Overlap) --","start":2269.534,"stop":2271.139,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You couldn't pass an ordinance but if this Illinois legislature vests either directly or by a whole rule charter, I don't know anything about Chicago.","start":2271.139,"stop":2281.582,"duration":10.44},{"text":"If a state vests licensing power in the City Council and it exercises that licensing power for a wholly arbitrary reason, I should think judicial review would apply to that just the same as those to commission of licenses (Voice Overlap) --","start":2281.582,"stop":2295.501,"duration":13.92}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Only -- only if it were unconstitutional.","start":2295.501,"stop":2298.984,"duration":3.48}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well -- or if it's -- it's unconstitutional if it's arbitrary --","start":2298.984,"stop":2302.028,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":2302.028,"stop":2302.126,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They say we won't give this to a Jew or a Catholic or a Negro.","start":2302.126,"stop":2306.755,"duration":4.63},{"text":"You could go into the federal court and say that's an unconstitutional exercise of power.","start":2306.755,"stop":2310.296,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, certainly, certainly.","start":2310.296,"stop":2311.591,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":2311.591,"stop":2314.276,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"However, it's doubtful whether if they -- if they said \"We're not going to let any Negroes have barber licenses.”","start":2314.276,"stop":2321.78,"duration":7.5},{"text":"You wouldn't need to apply for a license.","start":2321.78,"stop":2323.277,"duration":1.5},{"text":"You could go into federal court and get -- get an injunction tomorrow I assume.","start":2323.277,"stop":2327.627,"duration":4.35}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All these -- all of my questions are directed to the suggestion that if there is power in the state and the City has power because it's given by the state, then I don't think it can make a difference whether it's vested in an agency that is much more amenable, that is more amenable to political influence than some other agencies.","start":2327.627,"stop":2352.933,"duration":25.31}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I want to -- maybe I can answer that as I cast on to something else.","start":2352.933,"stop":2355.897,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, don't bother about it.","start":2355.897,"stop":2356.925,"duration":1.03},{"text":"You've dealt with it adequately.","start":2356.925,"stop":2360.775,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, I want to go now to a question that has been raised as to the status of Parmelee case.","start":2360.775,"stop":2367.346,"duration":6.57},{"text":"Now in the -- that has been adverted to by counsel for the Interstate Commerce Commission.","start":2367.346,"stop":2371.728,"duration":4.38},{"text":"The sole question in that case was whether the employees of Parmelee were by virtue of the arrangement between Parmelee and the Railroads if that make those employees, railroad employees, so that they were entitled to the benefits of the Railroad Labor Act.","start":2371.728,"stop":2390.821,"duration":19.09},{"text":"And the Interstate Commerce Commission, resting its decision squarely and entirely within the framework of the federal statutes said that -- that Parmelee was not a carrier in and of itself subject to the Interstate Commerce Act.","start":2390.821,"stop":2412.828,"duration":22.01},{"text":"Therefore, its employees were not employees of a carrier subject to the Interstate Commerce Act.","start":2412.828,"stop":2419.215,"duration":6.39},{"text":"But that case is precisely what I was saying this morning, namely, that the activities of -- of Transfer are simply assimilated to the operations of the railroads specifically by 202 (c) (2), they are made railroad operation.","start":2419.215,"stop":2440.057,"duration":20.84},{"text":"Now, however, I want to call your attention to other decisions of the Interstate Commerce Commission in respect to 202 (c) (2) of the Interstate Commerce Act.","start":2440.057,"stop":2456.345,"duration":16.29},{"text":"In pick up of livestock in Illinois Island and Wisconsin and I'm -- I'm referring now briefly to some cases on pages 31 -- 21 to 23 of our brief.","start":2456.345,"stop":2467.605,"duration":11.26},{"text":"In pick up of livestock in Illinois Island and Wisconsin, the railroads filed tariffs providing for pick up of livestock within 10 miles of their stations that is they'd -- they'd go out and bring them in and load them in cars.","start":2467.605,"stop":2483.872,"duration":16.27},{"text":"This was before the enactment of 202 (c).The -- that matter was brought before the Commission by a complaint of some motor carriers and the Commission said this that that was a motor carrier operation.","start":2483.872,"stop":2500.126,"duration":16.25},{"text":"The railroad had no authority under Part 2.","start":2500.126,"stop":2503.309,"duration":3.18},{"text":"It was not a railroad operation under Part 1.","start":2503.309,"stop":2505.535,"duration":2.23},{"text":"Therefore, the railroads were ordered to cancel their tariffs and cease and desist from the operation.","start":2505.535,"stop":2511.002,"duration":5.47},{"text":"After that, 202 (c) was enacted and the Commission reopened it.","start":2511.002,"stop":2516.569,"duration":5.57},{"text":"And then the Commission said the railroads now do not need any certificate under Part 2, 202 (c) has made it a railroad operation under part 1.","start":2516.569,"stop":2526.662,"duration":10.09},{"text":"We will now approve the tariffs of the railroads providing for pick up of livestock by motor truck within 10 miles of their stations.","start":2526.662,"stop":2534.309,"duration":7.65},{"text":"In other words, that shows by the construction of the Commission exactly the rights given by 202 (c) to the -- to the railroads that they are given in effect permanent certificates of public convenience and necessity to perform motor carrier operations, pick up and delivery and transfer in their terminal areas.","start":2534.309,"stop":2559.699,"duration":25.39},{"text":"Now, in cartridge rail, the steamship lines at New York.","start":2559.699,"stop":2566.982,"duration":7.28},{"text":"The railroads attempted to cancel tariffs.","start":2566.982,"stop":2572.231,"duration":5.25},{"text":"The railroads had filed tariffs providing for pickup and delivery in inter-station service of freight in New York.","start":2572.231,"stop":2580.224,"duration":7.99},{"text":"The railroads attempted to cancel those tariffs and the Commission held in that case that it had jurisdiction to require performance of the service.","start":2580.224,"stop":2589.614,"duration":9.39},{"text":"Now, any service that is performed under tariff and which the Commission has authority to require is a service that is, I submit, safe from any obstruction by state action, going again to another case of the Commission construing 202 (c), movement of highway trailers by rail.","start":2589.614,"stop":2618.541,"duration":28.93},{"text":"I'm sure you all take -- you've -- you've all read about it and take judicial notice of the fact that there is a tremendous railroad traffic growing up in what is so-called piggyback service.","start":2618.541,"stop":2630.304,"duration":11.76},{"text":"That is a trailer within a railroad terminal area that picks up freight.","start":2630.304,"stop":2635.962,"duration":5.66},{"text":"The trailer is hauled to the railroad yard and loaded on a flat car, carried by the flat car to destination.","start":2635.962,"stop":2641.18,"duration":5.22},{"text":"The trailer unloads it and it's delivered to destination.","start":2641.18,"stop":2644.531,"duration":3.35},{"text":"In a -- an extensive hearing before the Interstate Commerce Commission, the Commission held that that entire operation is railroad service subject to Part 1 of the Act and that in order to perform that service, the railroads do not need any authority under Part 2 on account of Section 202 (c).","start":2644.531,"stop":2665.075,"duration":20.54},{"text":"Now, if cities all along the line can impose obstructions and require a showing of public convenience and necessity for the transfer of property and the persons in terminal areas, 202 (c) and the intention of Congress in respect to it is completely set at naught.","start":2665.075,"stop":2685.62,"duration":20.55},{"text":"Now, I want to refer now to Castle against Hayes Freight Lines.","start":2685.62,"stop":2692.574,"duration":6.95},{"text":"No, I -- I will first refer to Columbia Terminal's case and the Bradley against the Public Utilities Commission.","start":2692.574,"stop":2699.937,"duration":7.36},{"text":"Now, both of those cases are immediately differentiated in this respect that the Columbia Terminal's case was decided before the enactment of Section 202 (c) of the Interstate Commerce Act.","start":2699.937,"stop":2717.013,"duration":17.08},{"text":"True enough, Columbia Terminals was performing inter-station pickup and delivery, but 202 (c) had not yet been enacted by the -- and that -- that is precisely the -- that the -- the District Court rested its decision on two grounds that there was no supersedure by the federal government.","start":2717.013,"stop":2737.994,"duration":20.98},{"text":"The federal government hadn't -- hadn't entered the field, the pick up and delivery service.","start":2737.994,"stop":2743.833,"duration":5.84},{"text":"In Bradley against Public Utilities Commission, it again rested on the ground that the federal government had not entered the field.","start":2743.833,"stop":2750.678,"duration":6.84},{"text":"Now, I want to go to Castle against Hayes Freight Lines because I think that case is directly in point here.","start":2750.678,"stop":2758.53,"duration":7.85},{"text":"Castle against Hayes Freight Lines involved an Illinois statute in which the State of Illinois in an attempt to avoid and abuse of its highways as the Court pointed out by overloading -- chronic overloading of motor trucks.","start":2758.53,"stop":2775.748,"duration":17.22},{"text":"The State passed an Act that a chronic overloader could be suspended from the use of the Illinois highways for 10 days for -- for three months and on the second offense prolonged.And this Court held that since Castle had a certificate from the Interstate Commerce Commission under which it was required to perform service and in as much as the Interstate Commerce Commission had the power to suspend that certificate that a power -- a -- an assertive power of suspension of Castle's rights in the state was violative of the Commerce Clause and the Interstate Commerce Act.","start":2775.748,"stop":2809.723,"duration":33.97},{"text":"You have precisely the same situation here because the railroads are vested with this right to perform the inter-station transfer service by Section 202 (c) (2) of the Interstate Commerce Act and there is this however this difference that did not appear in the Castle case.","start":2809.723,"stop":2831.36,"duration":21.64},{"text":"To the Hayes Freight Lines could file a cancellation of its schedules and could cease all operations in 30 days and the Interstate Commerce Commission or nobody else could do anything about it.","start":2831.36,"stop":2845.649,"duration":14.29},{"text":"If the railroads filed a cancellation of their tariffs providing for the inter-station transfer of railroad passengers, the Commission under its own holdings, no Court has passed on this but the Commission has so held in the case I cite.","start":2845.649,"stop":2859.748,"duration":14.1},{"text":"The Interstate Commerce Commission could compel the continuance of that inter-station transfer service.","start":2859.748,"stop":2866.273,"duration":6.53},{"text":"So in the Castle case, you held that a carrier who was not required, who was authorized, it's true to render service under the Interstate Commerce Act but was not required to do so could not be interfered with by the state on purely safety grounds, nothing but sheer police power grounds.","start":2866.273,"stop":2890.359,"duration":24.09},{"text":"But here, you have a case where the service -- the Commission as held can be compelled.","start":2890.359,"stop":2897.229,"duration":6.87},{"text":"We can't quit if the Interstate Commerce Commission says we can't quit.","start":2897.229,"stop":2902.656,"duration":5.43},{"text":"Yet, the City of Chicago purports to say that it is going to say who shall -- who the railroad shall make a contract with.","start":2902.656,"stop":2912.346,"duration":9.69}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- what is it that Chicago is trying to do that bars the railroads from carrying out the mandated of the Commission, its mandated to be that it should give in the Court inter-station transport?","start":2912.346,"stop":2928.422,"duration":16.08},{"text":"What is it that Chicago has done or seeks to do that precludes the railroad from doing what the Commissioner says they're required to do namely to carry people from one station to another?","start":2928.422,"stop":2941.808,"duration":13.39}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"The City of Chicago is doing exactly what the State of New York did in Gibbons against Ogden.","start":2941.808,"stop":2947.187,"duration":5.38},{"text":"It said -- it is saying \"Nobody shall render this inter-station transfer service for the railroads unless we approve them.\"","start":2947.187,"stop":2955.616,"duration":8.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But if I -- if I come into Chicago and I want to go from one station to another to get to New York or to Boston, is there anything that Chicago has -- is trying to do that precludes my getting that service from the railroad?","start":2955.616,"stop":2973.881,"duration":18.26},{"text":"Is there anything that Chicago is doing that precludes my getting a service which the Interstate Commerce Commission says I'm entitled to get, to have myself taken from one station to another?","start":2973.881,"stop":2984.925,"duration":11.04}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes, if the --","start":2984.925,"stop":2985.923,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What is it?","start":2985.923,"stop":2987.64,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"If the -- if the Chicago ordinance should be held valid then we've got -- then -- then we either have to go back to doing business with Transfer or we can't transfer the passengers.","start":2987.64,"stop":3003.885,"duration":16.25}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but Chicago doesn't say you can't have some rent for service carrying me.","start":3003.885,"stop":3009.941,"duration":6.06},{"text":"It merely -- it merely defines the choice you have as to who should be doing that service.","start":3009.941,"stop":3014.879,"duration":4.94}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that is correct and that is unconstitutional under every decision of this Court.","start":3014.879,"stop":3019.456,"duration":4.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But that wasn't -- that isn't what the -- what's the name of that in Chicago, in the Illinois case?","start":3019.456,"stop":3024.434,"duration":4.98},{"text":"The Hayes case was.","start":3024.434,"stop":3026.57,"duration":2.14},{"text":"With the Hayes case, with the latter certificate, he could do business and Illinois said, “No, you can't do business anymore.”","start":3026.57,"stop":3034.213,"duration":7.64}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, my associate called me to one point that I should have mentioned before.","start":3034.213,"stop":3038.512,"duration":4.3},{"text":"Sorry, I didn't.","start":3038.512,"stop":3041.972,"duration":3.46},{"text":"In the interchange -- and -- and that is in our complaint, and alleged in great detail and admitted of course by the motion for summary judgment.","start":3041.972,"stop":3052.114,"duration":10.14},{"text":"The railroads coming into Chicago have certain schedules to meet.","start":3052.114,"stop":3055.168,"duration":3.05},{"text":"That is taking a passenger from one station to another station.","start":3055.168,"stop":3060.522,"duration":5.35},{"text":"The railroads want to control that service to give good service to the passengers.","start":3060.522,"stop":3067.366,"duration":6.84},{"text":"The -- besides all of the considerations in the express language of 202 (c) (2), the railroads have a right as the Court of Appeals pointed out to select their own agent where the railroads are, at least a number of railroad presidents have said so, are fighting a very battle for their very lives and the passenger service is one of their most vulnerable points.","start":3067.366,"stop":3093.862,"duration":26.5},{"text":"And certainly, the railroads in their relations with the public and in maintaining their passenger service have a right to say who shall carry their passengers from one Chicago station to another.","start":3093.862,"stop":3108.188,"duration":14.33},{"text":"And in the maintenance of -- and have a carrier who will take a passenger from the Northwestern station to the Illinois Central Station some two miles away and getting there in time to catch the train for Springfield in New Orleans.","start":3108.188,"stop":3122.623,"duration":14.43},{"text":"That I think is the -- is the consideration and the -- the -- may I call your attention again to the -- the Hill against Florida covers, Your Honors, exact point as I understand it.","start":3122.623,"stop":3139.955,"duration":17.33},{"text":"In Hill against Florida, the State of Florida, a licensed representative of labor unions and said, “Nobody can be a bargaining agent for a labor union in the State of Florida unless he's licensed by the State of Florida.”","start":3139.955,"stop":3157.403,"duration":17.45},{"text":"On this case, this Court said the State of Florida can't do that, that employees have a right to be represented before the National Labor Relations Board and in the bargaining under the National Labor Relations Act have a right to be represented by their own representatives and that -- that the State of Florida simply cannot interfere with that right by demanding a license and that's exactly --","start":3157.403,"stop":3180.503,"duration":23.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll put it to you, Mr. Matthews.","start":3180.503,"stop":3181.848,"duration":1.34},{"text":"In the Hill case, this Court held that Congress had laid down certain conditions, certain qualifications for officers of the union and further tried to add that too.","start":3181.848,"stop":3200.06,"duration":18.21},{"text":"And this Court said, when Congress says conditions one, two, three of the conditions, it's presumably thought those were all the conditions that were necessary and part of that Act, four or five.","start":3200.06,"stop":3214.189,"duration":14.13},{"text":"Now, what I want to know is what conditions does the Interstate Commerce actually have done here other than to say that in a situation like Chicago, you may engage in inter-station transfer.","start":3214.189,"stop":3232.255,"duration":18.07},{"text":"It is authorizing to give that service but what have it said about choosing the means of carrying out that service.","start":3232.255,"stop":3246.235,"duration":13.98}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"It hadn't said anything in specific terms.","start":3246.235,"stop":3248.919,"duration":2.68},{"text":"I grant you that.","start":3248.919,"stop":3249.865,"duration":0.95},{"text":"But it has said that the -- the person you can -- you can make a contract with a person and then he becomes your service.","start":3249.865,"stop":3258.026,"duration":8.16},{"text":"And certainly, the Commerce Clause and the Interstate Commerce Act gives the railroads, I think just on the bear statement of it, gives the railroads the right to say who that agent shall be.","start":3258.026,"stop":3275.043,"duration":17.02},{"text":"That is my position on that.","start":3275.043,"stop":3276.168,"duration":1.13},{"text":"Now --","start":3276.168,"stop":3276.458,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- that's your total argument on the statute, isn't that true?","start":3276.458,"stop":3280.041,"duration":3.58}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3280.041,"stop":3281.109,"duration":1.07},{"text":"Well --","start":3281.109,"stop":3281.925,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It depends on the interpretation then of the statute.","start":3281.925,"stop":3284.78,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Of -- of the federal statute.","start":3284.78,"stop":3286.574,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Your argument?","start":3286.574,"stop":3287.513,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3287.513,"stop":3287.92,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that's what I mean.","start":3287.92,"stop":3289.078,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3289.078,"stop":3290.523,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You insist that that is the equivalent of saying the railroads shall have the right to make a contract with such a person or agent that you see fit to carry these passengers.","start":3290.523,"stop":3304.755,"duration":14.23}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":3304.755,"stop":3306.2,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And if you're wrong in that interpretation, you have to go back to your constitutional ground.","start":3306.2,"stop":3312.108,"duration":5.91}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3312.108,"stop":3312.705,"duration":0.6},{"text":"And I think it would -- I think we can -- I was about to touch on that -- the --","start":3312.705,"stop":3317.473,"duration":4.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Before you get to that, I want to ask you whether you do not also agree unless I misapprehended your argument in 103 that complies to use of this ordinance lies in the fact that Parmelee, by a practical operation, is given the grandfather license.","start":3317.473,"stop":3336.558,"duration":19.09},{"text":"And therefore, I ask whether that provision was out so that Parmelee would stand on the same footing or Transfer would stand on the same footing as everybody else, namely, for police reasons as I call it or traffic conditions, etcetera.","start":3336.558,"stop":3353.587,"duration":17.03},{"text":"Everybody has to get a license and nobody gets an advantage, you'd have a different situation, wouldn't you?","start":3353.587,"stop":3361.399,"duration":7.81}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not -- not under the constitution, no, I don't believe you would.","start":3361.399,"stop":3365.041,"duration":3.64},{"text":"However, we -- we are making no objection that grandfather clause to Parmelee.","start":3365.041,"stop":3369.31,"duration":4.27},{"text":"That, I don't think that is -- is an issue in the case.","start":3369.31,"stop":3371.716,"duration":2.41},{"text":"The merely is descriptive of what the City Council did.","start":3371.716,"stop":3374.938,"duration":3.22},{"text":"They gave -- but -- but on connection, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, with -- with what you've recently said.","start":3374.938,"stop":3383.575,"duration":8.64},{"text":"I want to go back to case of a venerable history namely the Pensacola Telegraph case.","start":3383.575,"stop":3390.858,"duration":7.28},{"text":"There, the State of Florida simply said “no telegraph company can come in to the state unless it has a license from the state.”","start":3390.858,"stop":3399.61,"duration":8.75},{"text":"And Congress, for the express purpose of avoiding that, provided for federal licenses for telegraph companies and this Court held that the Florida law couldn't keep the Western Union Telegraph out.","start":3399.61,"stop":3417.926,"duration":18.32},{"text":"Now as I say, the -- the question of who shall conduct Interstate Commerce is the important question in all of these cases from Gibbons against Ogden on down.","start":3417.926,"stop":3430.281,"duration":12.36},{"text":"I want to refer now to some couple of other federal statutes.","start":3430.281,"stop":3439.947,"duration":9.67},{"text":"In 1866, Congress passed an Act that has been variously called the -- the \"Railroad Communication Interchange Act of 1866.\"","start":3439.947,"stop":3450.582,"duration":10.63},{"text":"I set it out on page 26 in my brief.","start":3450.582,"stop":3454.712,"duration":4.13},{"text":"Now, the legislative history of that Act shows that the State of New Jersey had provided by a New Jersey law had -- had granted an exclusive franchise to a certain railroad and said that no other railroad could operate between Philadelphia and New York, which of course are both outside of the State of New Jersey, unless the legislature of New Jersey agreed.","start":3454.712,"stop":3491.622,"duration":36.91},{"text":"Congress passed the -- a law which says this and I think it's entirely applicable to this situation today, \"Every railroad company in the United States is hereby authorized to carry upon and over its road and so forth, passengers on their way from any state to another state and to receive compensation therefore and to connect with roads of other states so as to form continuous lines for the transportation of the same to the place of destination.\"","start":3491.622,"stop":3525.571,"duration":33.95},{"text":"And this Court has construed that Act in a number of cases, in the Bowman against the Chicago and Northwestern Railroad.","start":3525.571,"stop":3535.24,"duration":9.67},{"text":"The Court said, these Acts referring to that another Act were passed under the power vested in Congress were designed to remove trammels upon transportation between different states which had previously existed and to prevent a creation of such trammels in the future and to facilitate railway transportation.","start":3535.24,"stop":3556.21,"duration":20.97},{"text":"In Union Pacific against Rock Island Railroad cited on page 30, the Court said, “It is impossible for us to ignore the great public policy in favor of continuous lines thus declared by Congress and that such it is in effectuation of that policy that such business arrangements as it will make such connections effective are made.”","start":3556.21,"stop":3582.323,"duration":26.11},{"text":"Coming now to the last --","start":3582.323,"stop":3591.941,"duration":9.62}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you say to Mr. Kurland's argument for this event?","start":3591.941,"stop":3598.266,"duration":6.33},{"text":"It's been frequently held that at least in some cases and I thought (Inaudible) that the mere fact that Congress has the power to regulate in the absence of regulation, the powers don't with the state (Inaudible).","start":3598.266,"stop":3619.509,"duration":21.24},{"text":"And Mr. Kurland's argument, as I understood it, in reference to the statute was this, one argument.","start":3619.509,"stop":3625.794,"duration":6.28},{"text":"That the statute does give the Commission power to regulate it under one, Part 1 of the Act as a carrier, although it's not a carrier but it gives that regulatory.","start":3625.794,"stop":3637.346,"duration":11.55},{"text":"But they haven't made any effort to do it and therefore the power lines don't -- you can't claim that -- the city without a power by the state, without power to demand a certificate of convenience and necessity.","start":3637.346,"stop":3651.903,"duration":14.56},{"text":"What do you say to that argument?","start":3651.903,"stop":3653.268,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that argument is unsound on two bases.","start":3653.268,"stop":3656.991,"duration":3.72},{"text":"In the first place, the Congress has exercised the power here.","start":3656.991,"stop":3665.021,"duration":8.03},{"text":"In other words, if it were not for Section 202 (c) (2), the railroads could not conduct this inter-station transfer operation without a certificate of public convenience and necessity from the Commission under Part 2.","start":3665.021,"stop":3680.452,"duration":15.43},{"text":"But the Congress has given the railroads permanent motor carrier authority rights under Section 202 (c) (2).","start":3680.452,"stop":3694.641,"duration":14.19},{"text":"They -- they've given them just as effective rights as Hayes Freight Lines had so Congress has entered the field.","start":3694.641,"stop":3704.508,"duration":9.87},{"text":"The second answer to that is that assuming for purpose of argument that Congress has not entered the field, there is a very long line of cases.","start":3704.508,"stop":3716.733,"duration":12.23},{"text":"I cite them on Page 37 to the effect that no state or municipality can exercise its discretion as to whether it is going to permit the performance of Interstate Commerce.","start":3716.733,"stop":3739.92,"duration":23.19},{"text":"And under the cases, this Court in 140 years, the question of who is going to perform Interstate Commerce as between two rival candidates is a function that is forbidden to the states by the Commerce Clause so this Court has held.","start":3739.92,"stop":3760.98,"duration":21.06}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I understood maybe I was wrong about this argument but maybe I didn't make it briefly and clearly.","start":3760.98,"stop":3766.766,"duration":5.79},{"text":"I understood it not to deny that Congress had entered the field and authorized the Commission to regulate where he said it hadn't done so.","start":3766.766,"stop":3777.837,"duration":11.07}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he's in error about that because the -- the Commission has already exercised this authority.","start":3777.837,"stop":3789.343,"duration":11.51},{"text":"Of course the Commission exercised its authority in given situations but if it exercised its authority in New York in a precisely similar situation to the Chicago situation then the Commission certainly has entered the field of regulation.","start":3789.343,"stop":3804.308,"duration":14.97}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Has it established any rules supervising the selection of agents by the railroad?","start":3804.308,"stop":3810.883,"duration":6.57}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3810.883,"stop":3810.961,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I understood him to say it hadn't done that.","start":3810.961,"stop":3813.364,"duration":2.4}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir, it has not.","start":3813.364,"stop":3814.532,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Maybe I'm -- maybe I'm wrong about the (Voice Overlap) --","start":3814.532,"stop":3815.967,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, it has not.","start":3815.967,"stop":3816.835,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I gather that the argument was and since it hadn't done so, you couldn't claim that the statute is the equivalent of a certificate that the power is there lying dormant.","start":3816.835,"stop":3827.004,"duration":10.17}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it has not done so but it has said that it can compel the railroads to perform the service and it has compelled them to perform it.","start":3827.004,"stop":3839.193,"duration":12.19},{"text":"And if the railroads are compelled to perform it, the railroads certainly have the power to select under the -- the contracting party to perform it for them.","start":3839.193,"stop":3849.194,"duration":10},{"text":"They can't be deprived of that.","start":3849.194,"stop":3851.028,"duration":1.83},{"text":"Perhaps Congress could deprive them of that power but certainly the states and local governments can't deprive them of that power.","start":3851.028,"stop":3859.341,"duration":8.31}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Matthews, tell me why I'm wrong in thinking as you talk that 202 (c) (2) in effect says \"You don't need to get a license with the federal government.\"","start":3859.341,"stop":3877.834,"duration":18.49}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Because --","start":3877.834,"stop":3878.443,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't that true?","start":3878.443,"stop":3879.691,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3879.691,"stop":3880.966,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Because it says -- it says 202, although you're a trucker, you don't have to get a trucker's license what other truckers have to get.","start":3880.966,"stop":3887.926,"duration":6.96}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3887.926,"stop":3890.092,"duration":2.17},{"text":"I -- I disagree with your construction.","start":3890.092,"stop":3891.078,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, tell me why that's wrong.","start":3891.078,"stop":3892.695,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"It -- its wrong for this reason that it says that despite in effect, it says despite the -- the provisions of Part 1, you are hereby authorized to go ahead and operate and to make contracts with another to operate for you, pick up and delivery service in inter-station areas.","start":3892.695,"stop":3920.126,"duration":27.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You may make that selection and you don't have to come to the Interstate Commerce Commission the way other people who do that service do have to come and get a license on under two.","start":3920.126,"stop":3930.526,"duration":10.4}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I'm -- under two I -- I --","start":3930.526,"stop":3932.51,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Under Part 2 of the 1940 Act.","start":3932.51,"stop":3936.223,"duration":3.71},{"text":"Section 202 (c) (2) released these inter-station carriers from getting -- from being required to get the license that are under Part 2 of the Transportation Act as required by other people who do that kind of thing.","start":3936.223,"stop":3952,"duration":15.78}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Section 202 (c) (2) doesn't give any rights to the inter-station carrier itself but it does give rights to the railroads.","start":3952,"stop":3960.742,"duration":8.74}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3960.742,"stop":3961.221,"duration":0.48},{"text":"But the question is what's the nature of their ideas --","start":3961.221,"stop":3963.966,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Their nature --","start":3963.966,"stop":3964.313,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and the scope of it and I say that although we've got a provision of the Transportation Act which said that a person who does -- who does the interstate carriage of the kind that inter-station service people do in Chicago, they do not need a license.","start":3964.313,"stop":3988.207,"duration":23.89}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think the answer to that is this.","start":3988.207,"stop":3991.578,"duration":3.37},{"text":"That the railroads are performing transportation under Part 1 of the Interstate Commerce Act and they are part of the service.","start":3991.578,"stop":4007.415,"duration":15.84},{"text":"They are required to perform and were required to perform before 202 (c) was enacted is the transfer of freight and passengers between their stations.","start":4007.415,"stop":4022.011,"duration":14.6},{"text":"They have been doing that for many years in a case that's involving the transfer in St.Louis.","start":4022.011,"stop":4032.174,"duration":10.16},{"text":"I cited the case before 202 (c) was enacted.","start":4032.174,"stop":4036.456,"duration":4.28},{"text":"This Court held that a contract of this character between a railroad -- between the St.Louis Railroads and an inter-station carrier could not be enjoined under the antitrust laws because it was within that exemption from injunction under the Antitrust laws any -- of any right arising under the Interstate Commerce Act.","start":4036.456,"stop":4061.635,"duration":25.18},{"text":"And this Court --","start":4061.635,"stop":4062.004,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What is -- what is your answer to Justice Frankfurter?","start":4062.004,"stop":4064.639,"duration":2.64},{"text":"It's not quite clear what you said here that they do not have to get a license on the federal government to this -- this particular motor carrier --","start":4064.639,"stop":4075.287,"duration":10.65}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Transfer.","start":4075.287,"stop":4075.614,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- doesn't have to get it.","start":4075.614,"stop":4076.892,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":4076.892,"stop":4077.569,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Does that -- does that end your case so far as the Act is concerned?","start":4077.569,"stop":4081.17,"duration":3.6},{"text":"If the Congress has constitutionally given you the power to make the selection, what is the difference?","start":4081.17,"stop":4090.199,"duration":9.03}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm afraid I don't understand your question, sir.","start":4090.199,"stop":4091.684,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What if Congress had given you the power to make the selection of somebody to do the carrying?","start":4091.684,"stop":4098.731,"duration":7.05},{"text":"Why?","start":4098.731,"stop":4099.22,"duration":0.49},{"text":"What difference does that make to your contention?","start":4099.22,"stop":4101.187,"duration":1.97},{"text":"Would you not still claim that the City can't take away that power?","start":4101.187,"stop":4105.666,"duration":4.48}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's what we do claim.","start":4105.666,"stop":4107.193,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought so.","start":4107.193,"stop":4108.938,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- well, I may -- I may have misspoken.","start":4108.938,"stop":4112.219,"duration":3.28},{"text":"The Congress has given us.","start":4112.219,"stop":4114.625,"duration":2.41},{"text":"Congress didn't exempt us from anything in 202 (c).","start":4114.625,"stop":4119.314,"duration":4.69},{"text":"The Congress gave the railroads who were engaging in commerce the right to continue that commerce, a permanent -- a permanent certificate by statute.","start":4119.314,"stop":4131.403,"duration":12.09}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"By a contract.","start":4131.403,"stop":4132.768,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":4132.768,"stop":4133.417,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Select somebody by a contract.","start":4133.417,"stop":4134.992,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"Or they can do it themselves without -- or they can -- or they can select somebody by contract, yes.","start":4134.992,"stop":4141.647,"duration":6.65}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And maybe that's not the equivalent of a certificate that they had authorized.","start":4141.647,"stop":4147.394,"duration":5.75},{"text":"But isn't that your point now or is it that that's the equivalent of an authority granted by the Interstate Commerce Commission on certificate of convenience and necessity is that they had the power to give it, that it has authorized you to get somebody to do that.","start":4147.394,"stop":4162.54,"duration":15.15}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":4162.54,"stop":4163.057,"duration":0.52},{"text":"That is my point.","start":4163.057,"stop":4163.754,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't need a statute.","start":4163.754,"stop":4165.707,"duration":1.95},{"text":"The answer -- the suggested answer is that 202 (c) (2) is immaterial because the Commerce Clause gives you that untrammeled choice, isn't that right?","start":4165.707,"stop":4180.493,"duration":14.79}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"No, well under Part 2, we need 202 (c) because Part 2 is on the statute.","start":4180.493,"stop":4191.242,"duration":10.75},{"text":"If it wasn't for 202 (c), we'd have to apply for a certificate under Part 2 of the Interstate Commerce Act.","start":4191.242,"stop":4195.593,"duration":4.35}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Forget about applied in 1940.","start":4195.593,"stop":4198.718,"duration":3.13},{"text":"If you claim this as an exercise of the -- as a right to carry on interstate commerce into which the state can't cut it, isn't that right?","start":4198.718,"stop":4211.371,"duration":12.65}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":4211.371,"stop":4214.094,"duration":2.72},{"text":"Well, I -- I -- we claim under both that -- that --","start":4214.094,"stop":4217.186,"duration":3.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that but -- but if --","start":4217.186,"stop":4220.777,"duration":3.59}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"But in --","start":4220.777,"stop":4220.935,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- if it's under the Commerce Clause that no statute can save it.","start":4220.935,"stop":4225.454,"duration":4.52}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't understand that, sir.","start":4225.454,"stop":4226.59,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If you have a right under the Commerce Clause then no statute can take it away, no state statute can take it away.","start":4226.59,"stop":4234.183,"duration":7.59}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":4234.183,"stop":4235.069,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And that is your position.","start":4235.069,"stop":4236.466,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"It's our position that's --","start":4236.466,"stop":4237.345,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what (Voice Overlap) of your position.","start":4237.345,"stop":4238.551,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Amos M. Matthews","textObjs":[{"text":"We're -- that that's right.","start":4238.551,"stop":4239.717,"duration":1.17},{"text":"We rely first on the stronger position that Congress has superseded the power of the state but -- that even if Congress hadn't superseded the power of the state, we would still have the power.","start":4239.717,"stop":4247.874,"duration":8.16},{"text":"Yes, that is our position under these various federal statutes.","start":4247.874,"stop":4254.958,"duration":7.08}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Kurland.","start":4254.958,"stop":4256.762,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Court has a question --","start":4256.762,"stop":4258.287,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":4258.287,"stop":4259.991,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"Philip B. Kurland","textObjs":[{"text":"-- give you back the rest of the time.","start":4259.991,"stop":4262.496,"duration":2.51},{"text":"Thank you very much.","start":4262.496,"stop":4263.324,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Kurland.","start":4263.324,"stop":4267.526,"duration":4.2}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Mar  5 - 6, 1958","petitioner":"City of Chicago","respondent":"Atchison, Topeka & Santa Fe Railway Company","docket":"103","citation":"357 US 77 (1958)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/357/77","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jun 16, 1958"}